product_title: Hot Wheels RC Terrain Twister
review_headline: Monster RC toy with crazy hard direction control
review_body:
This RC control monster is HUGE! A lot bigger than I thought. It is more than twice as big as my shoe box.

This toy came with batteries and rechargeable battery pack. Initial charging time is about 2 hours. Battery assembly is a little tricky but not hard.

The toy advertised as "no terrain is too tough for this R/C vehicle" but in fact it is hard to maneuver this vehicle on smooth and flat surface. It is best to play this on the rough surface/terrain for best traction. It is hard to control this monster also because the battery packed a lot of power. Any push on the remote control and the vehicle moved really fast and hard. I am a little worried about the rechargeable battery compartment. It is not water proof. So in a slightly rough water I am afraid the water can get inside and damage the battery pack. One other problem I noticed too is like other reviewer said, this thing does not go straight line and it doesn't not turn easily if you are playing on flat surface.

product_title: Fairytale Gloom
review_headline: Fun game that could be better
review_body:
I saw this game at Comic-Con and played it briefly at one of the tables where they were demoing it. I've never played any of the Gloom games before and very much liked the idea of the transparent cards where you can play on top of your own or other people's piles to change the course of the game.

Now I've played it 8 times with 3-5 people. While the game is enjoyable, it has not completely lived up to my expectations. It seems to be the consensus position that it takes too long to play and most of the times I've played we all wished it were over sooner.

If 2 or more people gang up on someone, they can pretty much prevent them from making any forward progress in the game, or so we've found, and that person gets frustrated.

So fun game, cute cards and nice artwork, but just did not quite live up to what we were expecting.

product_title: Paw Patrol - Paw Patroller
review_body: I received this toy as part of a promotion.  It was a nice surprise for my kids.  The package came and I let them know it was for them - no birthdays, holidays or other special events were near.  So, they were excited to tear open such a HUGE box.  At first, they kids were a bit disappointed that the truck only comes with one pup and mini vehicle.  The box showed pictures of several Paw Patrol agents and because the box was so big, they just figured more than one character would be included.  They quickly got over that, however, and they LOVE this thing.  They ran and got other toys to add to the Patroller and played with it until dinner.  I couldn't believe they didn't start fighting over it.  It took them some time to figure out all of the neat things the Patroller could do and each time, they ran to me saying, "it can do this" or it can do that".  We received this toy 2 days before leaving for vacation.  We were gone for 2 weeks and the first thing they played with when we got back?  The Paw Patroller.  My 5 year old girl likes it, but it's truly the 8 and 9 year old boys that have been playing with it!

product_title: Lalaloopsy Mini Pet Pals Doll- Purrty Kitten Paws
review_body: I debated for a long time over whether to buy the full-size version of this adorable kitten Lalaloopsy ([[ASIN:B00EZIKVP2 Lalaloopsy Pet Pals Purrty Kitten Paws Doll]]) which, although quite cute, was a bit pricey; so I was very pleased to finally see a mini version on the market. She's just as cute as her full-size counterpart, much less expensive and fit in better with my collection of mini Lalaloopsies. Her packaging, as with the rest of the Lalaloopsy minis, has been simplified so that it no longer makes a play house when you remove the plastic partition; as a collector, this doesn't bother me, but if you're considering purchasing this item for a child that may be something you want to consider. Overall, I think the animal-themed twist on the usually human-like Lalaloopsy dolls is really adorable, and I hope they continue to make more!

product_title: LeapFrog Letter Factory Imagicards Learning Game and Bonus Booster Pack
review_body:
We have a ton of LeapPad games, some (mostly Disney-themed) get played often, others less so. All of them have a 15- to 30-minute shelf life unless the kids are trapped in the car.

This Imagicard system really changes that. By making the game tactile and interactive, the girls will play for over an hour easily. They think they're so cool taking pics with their LeapPad and the game is very forgiving and responsive, two things I was previously concerned about.

There's still a learning curve, as with all Leapster products, so I think 5+ is the right age to try it without a lot of parental help.

product_title: Loopdedoo Spinning Loom Kit Friendship Bracelet Maker
review_headline: The machine wasn't worth the fuss.
review_body:
It comes with a lot of thread, which makes it a decent deal. But it is exactly what you see in the pictures. There is a hook on either side of the machine, you wrap the threads back and forth between the hooks and there is a roller on the side that helps you to create bracelets. I was hoping this would be fun, or easier, as we used to make these as kids by hand. The hand way is just as easy. As my niece pulled it off the machine, she accidentally dropped it and it all unraveled anyway.

If you have a daughter or son that loves to make these bracelets, then it might be worth it. But it is just as easy to make them by hand. The machine for us wasn't worth the fuss.

product_title: Cards Against Humanity
review_body:
This game is extremely fun and a great party game! I bought the original set and the Extension Pack 1.

The object of the game is for the "player-in-charge", which rotates each round, to put down a card that often has a blank that needs to be filled in. Each player puts down a card that they feel best fills in the blank and answers the question, as well as what will appeal to the "host's" personality the most. The host doesn't see who puts down what card. The host picks their favorite response, and the person who put down that card gets to collect the host's question card. The person who collects the most question cards wins.

Many of these questions and answers are "dirty", or not PC, so it is not a good idea to play with someone who is easily offended. The more players you have, the more fun the game is.

This game is a study in character. You have to know something about each of the players' personalities and what types of responses would best appeal to them if you want the best shot at winning!

product_title: LEGO Juniors 10667 Construction
review_headline: Age range on the packaging label misses the mark
review_body: I'm giving this product a 2 star rating primarily because of the age range on the packaging.  We received this set and another LEGOS Juniors set for my son's 5th birthday.  The age range on the packages reads 4-7 years.  There is NO. WAY. a 4 or 5 year old could put these sets together.  Some of the parts are unbelievably small and my son could not even pick them up.  We had to quickly gather up the little bags and get them onto the kitchen table to be opened or we would have lost half the parts if he had dumped them on the floor of our living room like he was about to do (and don't most kids that age?).  It took my husband a good hour of cursing to put them together and then we had to tell our son he can only play with them in the kitchen or our 18 month old would definitely be swallowing parts.  I can see these getting played with when he's older but half the fun of LEGOS is building things yourself, not waiting for your parents to have time to build them for you.  It just seems to me the age range is way off for the size of the bricks.  Otherwise it's a cute set, just not for a 5 year old to enjoy building.  And now as parents we have the "fun" of having to rebuild the darn things every time he knocks a piece off or pulls it apart.  Seems like a waste to me.

product_title: The Ares Project Card Game
review_body: I feel like the first review posted here sells the game short a bit. While it's like Risk in that both games have dice, The Ares Project adds in quite a few other elements to combat. Units are divided into four types (infantry, armor, air, and buildings) and each unit has its own to-hit numbers for each of these unit types as well as special abilities (tough, shielded, deep strike, and others) in addition to positional modifiers, flanking modifiers, and other modifiers from special buildings or attached technologies/powers. It's very possible for a single well-placed force to decimate a larger force if you properly utilize the strengths and weaknesses built into the combat system.  Admittedly the basic rules are fairly simple and omit many of the special powers and buildings that add complexity to the game. However, the developers intended the basic rules to be a tutorial to help players get a grasp on the combat system before graduating to the full rules. Once the full rules are in play, each of the four factions takes on an asymmetrical aspect as each produces units, power, and upgrades differently. Each faction is designed with specific strengths and weaknesses and favors a certain play style.  The flavor of each faction is pretty strong (a force of Space Marines and their vehicles, a cabal of psychic wizards flinging elemental spells and hazards, ever-evolving insectoid Martians, and a gargantuan mecha) and creates a lot of amazing scenarios with a little imagination.  I would NOT describe this game as 'simple'. The rules do have a bit of a learning curve but that's because the game has depth. If you have a dedicated player you can learn the game with, there's a lot of replayability here.  One negative is that the art on the cards is a bit drab and simply shows the production building in an aerial view; images of the units produced by that building would probably have been nicer.  Other than that, this is a well-constructed game that captures the feel of RTS. Itplays best with 2 but has variants for 3 or 4. Be sure you have someone who can dedicate time to learning the game with you and it will be a solid addition to your collection.

product_title: UDI U818A Combo Bundle 2.4GHz 4 CH 6 Axis Gyro RC Quadcopter with Camera RTF Mode 2 (Extra set of rotors, battery, and TF card)
review_body:
Great quad, came with everything as expected. The 2gb cards run out of space quickly, I recommend getting a 16gb one to be safe. The batteries run out of power in around 7 -10 min, depends of the use. Bought a pack of 5 additionally and I get a fun hour of flying.
Crashed it a bunch of times already and It works fine still, no propellers broken.
Since is very very lightweight, can't be flown well under windy conditions. It has 2 modes ( one with more pitch degrees than the other) and the mode 2 is more useful under heavy wind, but still you'll be battling the weather because it is very lightweight.
For the price is very good to start on the quadcopter flying world and to learn about the physics involved.

product_title: LolliZ Luncheon Napkins, 12 Pcs Pink/White Polka Dots, 13" X 13" 2-Ply
review_headline: Main value is it matches an entire line of products
review_body:
I received these as a free review sample. This napkin is a bit pricey considering that there are far nicer ones available for a lot less.

Granted, these are functional and do the trick (plus, folded they are kid-sized and even thicker). The main value is if you are purchasing a complete set of party items that are available from this brand these are a perfect match. In fact, you would have to look long and hard to get the same motif in the exact color.

Know, too, that these are not only for kids. They are perfect (when combined with plates, cups and other items from this line) for baby showers and It's a Girl celebrations.

If you are planning a themed party of celebration where this design is appropriate, grab these along with the rest of the items mentioned. If you are looking for just napkins, you may want to continue looking.

product_title: Cool Baker Chocolate Treats Maker
review_body:
My 9 year old was so excited about this product. We received this through Buzz agent about a week ago, but just got around to it last night. I kept forgetting to pic up chocolate, since it did not come with any to start with. :)
Easy to snap together. The instructions for this were very clear. Also the instructions to create the chocolates, I thought, were clear as well.
I was impressed with how easy it was to melt the chips. A little hot water and away we went!
Easy for a 9 year old to work on their own. This is great, so she can do this with her friends with very little help from an adult. It makes them feel independent when they don't need any help.
I agree with some of the others, that the tool for 'painting' is not that greatest, or easy to use. I think also a couple more mixing spatulas would be nice, so you are not having to clean off the single spatula over and over again. The molds were cute. Hopefully, we can buy others, but I haven't looked yet. We immediately lost one of the sticks (probably down the sink) and there were only two so..... A pile of paper sticks would be better for this I think. This activity does take a little bit of practice. The first owl looked terrible, but the second was not too bad! :)
Overall a great little activity for a young girl. My daughter would give it 5 stars, but I am going with 4 for the reasons above.

product_title: Faber-Castell Triangular Colored EcoPencils - 24 Count
review_headline: Smooth, Bold, Rich Colors! Great for the Price!
review_body:
I was looking for a wide range of colored pencils I could use for some adult coloring books and some other art projects I had in mind and these ones in particular caught my eye because it looked as if there were plenty of bright and dark colors available. I will say that these are great quality pencils for the price. The colors come out very smooth and pigmented, especially the darker colors, and you don't have to press down too hard to get that deep color. Even if I did press down pretty hard the pencil wouldn't budge or break! The pencils are in a triangular shape so I would recommend that if you get these, you should also buy the Faber Castell Trio pencil sharpener to be safe. I'm not sure if any other sharpener for triangular-shaped pencils will work so I went ahead and ordered their brand of sharpener. They don't roll away because of their shape either.

I am giving it 4 out of 5 stars only because I had to find and order a particular pencil sharpener for these pencils. I HIGHLY suggest you order the both of them together, because I did not and you will definitely need it!

product_title: Tamiya Modeler's Knife Pro
review_body:
I seriously can't recommend this modeling knife enough to anyone that builds plamo. The fact that it comes with a curved blade is a big deal, and the weighted base of the knife helps keep you balanced and alleviates extreme strain when you're trimming parts. I've had mine for a long while now and haven't snapped a blade (knock on wood) for the life of the knife. My old xacto blade would snap every so often and this is a big money-saver for me in that sense.

It does take a little bit of getting used to if you're switching over from the typical xacto (since, again, this blade is weighted at the end) but once you've been using it for a while it becomes an extension of your hand. Plus, as I mentioned before, it comes with a variety of blades which are great for different types of builds.

Highly HIGHLY recommended! Well worth the price point!

review_headline: It's amazing that such a compact game can offer so much ...
review_body: It's amazing that such a compact game can offer so much fun!  We have a Family Dinner Night that usually concludes with some kind of game. product_title: TECHEGE  Toys 911 Fire Truck Emergency Response Team Fire Engine Ladder
review_headline: Sturdy truck with lights and sound, but the only kids it interested were the ones too young to play with it
review_body:
I live in a touristy beach-side town in the South and living here, my family descends upon me in the summer, including all the little ones. And because I live here, everyone looks to me to be well-prepared and the kids always look to me to have toys and amusements and little entertainments and then they get upset with me when I don't have them. And I don't have kids of my own, so there's no reason for me to have entertainments for them. So when I saw this fire truck, I thought it may give the smaller teacup humans something to do while the older ones played board games or went outside to play backyard games.

The truck arrived in a well-labeled and sturdy box with a handle attached to the top so that it could be easily carried around, even by the little ones. The truck itself is fairly sturdy. It uses 3 AA batteries (not included) in order to light up and play sounds. There is a rotating piece on the top and the six wheels on the bottom roll fairly easily. There's another set of wheels that can be uncovered with a removal of the cap on the underside of the truck. Although it's a nice truck, unfortunately, due to small pieces, it's not suitable for the littles under three years old who were the ones who really wanted to play with it and the littles over three lost interest in it fairly quickly because it didn't have enough compartments and moving features. I don't know if this is indicative of the item or I just happen to have a very fussy family and I have no insight on kids as a general population. Nice truck, but not a popular item in my household.

I received this truck for free in exchange for a genuine critique.

product_title: NSI Room Planetarium and Projector
review_headline: Also the dome come off easily. The second feature is the projector
review_body:
Maybe I had too high expectations, but this product is not really worth the money.

First: the dome with the stars is barely resembling the night sky; I was not expecting a 3d projector, but some sort of realistic image. Instead the dome is practically a film of plastic with transparent areas to resemble a star effect; not even my 5 year old was impressed by the effect. Also the dome come off easily.

The second feature is the projector...oh boy, what a joke. There are few disks, each contains 5-6 images. The projector is reflecting light on these, and magnify them. The problem is that the size of the image is ridicule; at most it fits on a dinner plate; unless you want to project it at further distance, where you will loose most of the details, because the image and the lens are not made to project it at great distance (like from the floor to the ceiling? Wow...).

A mediocre product; not even a child would enjoy this, to be honest.
Much better to invest in a portable projector, and hook it up to a pocket computer (like a raspberry pi), that stream real NASA pictures; I did make one spending less than 150 dollars, but you get a 1080p resolution that fill most of your ceiling, which is a whole different level from what you get from this item.

Unless your kids are very small (less than 5), they won't be really impressed, and for an adult, don't even bother.

review_body:
This is an exact replica of the infamous Grave Digger and anybody who has ever heard of or seen Monster trucks knows Grave Digger. You don't have be a loyal Monster truck fan to love Grave digger. How can you not love this truck? It's a shiny purple with the decals that are consistent with the ones worn by the legendary monster truck.
This is an extremely rugged electric vehicle on extremely high tires. Flames on the side with front and rear suspension with shock absorbers so you can stick even the higher jumps without damaging the body of the vehicle.
The tires are very wide and grooved so they ride on any terrain. It goes a nice speed and can turn back, front, right, or left so there is no place that has to go untraveled.
With rechargeable batteries Grave Digger can provide hours of fun everyday and you will not need to constantly buy replacement batteries. This would be a gift for a girl or boy because everybody enjoys a fast vehicle with flashing lights.
I received this product complimentary in exchange for my honest opinion but the opinion expressed is all my own.

product_title: Square Enix Variant Play Arts Kai Batman: Timeless - Wild West Action Figure
review_headline: As good or better than any detailed photo I've seen. Stunned!
review_body:
This is my first elaborate action figure purchase in this price range and size. I have to say I'm stunned by the quality and detail. As a professional western artist and a Batman comics/movie fan, my worlds collided with this figure when I first saw it by sheer chance. It's now August and I've been squirming since my pre-order in May. WELL worth the wait. The posing options are so numerous that I was surprised anyone could come up with this many. The minute detail is unbelievable. I have a closet full of 19th century western wear. Now this makes me want to add a few things to it.

The one thing that bothers, and certainly nothing I'd reduce stars for, is the clear plastic base that comes with this. It's sparkly reflective quality seems to go against this rustic old-style steampunkish figure. I'm going to see if I can find another in metal or at least in a dark color so that it blends with the figure without calling attention. If anyone's been collecting these for a while and has suggestions, I hope I see the comment here.

product_title: Mega Bloks Monster Moviemobile
review_body:
I got this for my niece to play with when she is here. She is 8 and loves Monster High!

Overall, this is a cute set. The colors are vibrant and the little figure is cute, but as others have mentioned Mega Bloks are sometimes iffy. We did encounter a few problems with blocks staying together in a tight fit, and unfortunately we've encountered that issue with every Mega Bloks set we've gotten. Some of the black bricks in the car, just didn't want to fit together. On the flip side, I had blocks that were so tightly fit we couldn't even pry them apart! That makes it hard for kids to view these as play sets, as opposed to models-meaning once you get it together you don't play with it or move it. Not what my kids are looking for in a toy like this.

While I like the whole Monster High concept-sometimes the quality of the sets leaves something to be desired.

product_title: CloudPets 12in - The Adorable, Huggable Pet to Keep in Touch through the Cloud … …
review_headline: My daughter and I are really enjoying this toy
review_body:
This bear is incredibly soft! I was going to save it as a gift for my daughter for the holidays but I caved. It's so cute I had to give it to her early.

Set up is easy. You install the app and once you've created an account, it walks you through it. You'll be prompted to install an update, then restart your pet.

Pros:
• Very soft plush material
• Can be used on android or Apple devices
- I have an iPhone & my husband has a Samsung and both worked well
• record & receive messages (your child can respond to you over the cloud)
• Extras in your child's menu:
• lullabies (Ba-Ba Black Sheep, This Old Man, Twinkle-Twinkle Little Star, Welsh Lullaby) that have multiple settings
• 5, 8, 10, 12, & 15 minutes
• low, medium, high volume
• 2 Read-A-Long stories
• Barnyard Sounds game
• Access your child's messages to send to your CloudPet

Cons:
• needs more in-depth instructions or walk/through on the app for invite recipients
- I helped my husband figure it out, but I'm pretty sure I'd need to show my mother or anyone else not as tech-savvy how to do it in person (p.s. don't tell my mom I said that about her :) )
• You need to manually go into your child's menu in the app to send any messages you've recorded or that others have sent (this could also be a "pro", but I was under the impression that if I sent it on my device while in Bluetooth range, it would send automatically)
• don't hold down the blue button too long while playing a message or it shorts out [perhaps] - you'll know if that's happened if you hear a feedback sound and the buttons are no longer responsive. ** this can be fixed by turning the CloudPet off, then back on again. Also easily avoided if you watch your kiddo with it & by not holding the button longer than necessary
• 10 second record time for mom/dad recording VS 18 seconds for your child to record a response. It would be nice to have an extended option for messages sent to child as well

** If you are using the app to set it up, watch for the heart to blink twice on your pet to confirm it has been connected...the written instructions tell you this; however, the application does not.

My daughter and I are really enjoying this toy, as well as the rest of my family. I hope they come out with some additional updates soon, but I am just as equally pleased with what this product can do.

* I purchased this product at a promotional discount for testing and evaluation purposes in exchange for my honest and unbiased review

I believe this product is of sound quality, but it does need a couple of small tweaks to make it closer to flawless.re using the app to set it up, watch for the heart to blink twice on your pet to confirm it has been connected...the written instructions tell you this; however, the application does not. product_title: Disney Character On-the-Go Bingo Game
review_body: First I gotta say, I bought this at Target for $3 in that little section you see when you first walk in the store.  I purchased it there July 2015.  Perfect for on the go.  We use this at restaurants, at the pool, waiting for car service. The pieces are small-travel game size.  There are 4 boards (4 3/4" x 4").  The 60 dime sized tokens are cardboard.  The 30 little picture cards are playing card paper material.  The boards are double sided.  We are a family of 4 with a 3yo and 6yo.  One drawback for the parents is that the names of the characters are not on the picture cards but if you're kids are like mine and know every Disney character imaginable then you won't have a problem if you don't know the name or get the name wrong.  Our 3yo was able to find the matching picture on the boards.  The pictures on the board are small but I'd expect that from a travel size game.  They seem to stand up to getting a little wet as we play this at the pool.  Our 3yo will have the tendency to bend the picture cards.  And it comes in a re-useable zip lock package.

product_title: Gymnic / Rody Inflatable Hopping Horse
review_body: We bought this for our 24 month old grandson.  He loves bouncing on it and then "falling" off onto the floor.  I bought it after watching him play with one at an indoor "jump" facility.  I figured that if it was durable enough to withstand hundreds of kids bouncing on it day after day, it would hold up well for home use.  It is made of a very thick rubber-type product.  You'll need a bicycle or hand pump to air it up, but once aired up, it seems to maintain its air.  The fill valve is at the rear of the horse and sits fairly flush with the horse, but even still, while at the indoor jump facility I observed a toddler open the valve with his teeth and deflate one, all in a matter of seconds.

product_title: Friendly Bands Mega Sunshine Loom Craft Kit
review_headline: The loom itself is very very sturdy. Each peg has two pegs within it which ...
review_body:
I will first start this by saying, this is not our first loom bracelet kit but, I do believe it will be our last. The loom itself is very very sturdy. Each peg has two pegs within it which I must say is much easier to work with than more traditional looms and you can get the hook in with less of a hassle. I think the set up of the loom allows for you to do more difficult designs without putting too much stress on the loom ( we've had a couple looms break for this reason). The bands are of great quality as well, I have yet to have one break where as normally I break at least 10 in the process of making one bracelet. The storage container for the bands sturdy and provides a lot of different compartments so you can organize them however you like. The hooks are sturdy plastic, not flimsy or easily bendable. I absolutely love this kit! Of all the looms kits and bits and pieces you can get for them this by far is the best I have yet to own and I really do not see this breaking for a long time if ever.
Disclaimer: I received this product free for my honest and unbiased opinion and I assure you that is what you have received.

review_body:
Marvel Mashems Squishy Toys Mystery 6-pack
I first want to say that I went through and read some of the other comments on this and a few said that they think that this is way over priced for what you get. which honestly it is not because if you were to do up to your local store and check out the pricing on these they run about $4 a piece. And second to the ones saying they are disappointed about getting the same characters that is just something you take a chance with when buying these and what makes them really fun always trying to get the ones that you don't have.
I honestly love this bundle because you do get 6 packs and yes a chance of getting the same ones but its always fun for the kids opening them seeing which character they have gotten this time.
Also these are great not only for them to play with because they are squishy and bouncy, but they are also nice for collecting. My kids love getting different mystery packs and keeping them put up in their little cases.

It took a lot of elbow grease and TLC to fix their hair. Clawdeen also had greasy hair which I had to fix, and several black smears on her face and neck which I had to remove with acetone. Draculaura's hair was also a mess, but nothing that a wash and re-style couldn't fix. In the end, I ended up with a great set of dolls, but it took a lot of work to get there. product_title: Diy oil painting, paint by number kit - Abstract tree 16*20 inch.
review_body: Pure Junk! The canvas is made up with lines (not the drawn ones) that are hard to paint over they are like stitched lines in the plastic fabric. So it leaves a jagged streak under the paint making small areas and corners hard to get a straight edge. It also comes with tiny 'TINY' paint pot supplies so you will need to go to a craft store to get more 'before you paint'. I started painting and the paint included has a thicker and glossy shine. The cloth canvas comes through so even with thick paint you need to go over it a few times. The paint I used from home, as close to the color that came (most of all the black) is very lackluster compared to the paint it came in. The canvas is very hard to read and there is lettering at the bottom right hand side making it look tacky (see photo) the brushes are actually great and it came with a free sticker. But it basically was a cheap 'made in China' dollar store style set. The writing/spelling on the box is wrong... If you buy this please do yourself a major solid and buy paint from a craft store prior. Stick to one style paint so you won't get the flat to lackluster mess mix I created tonight. It's not letting my upload my photo. But yes, there is lettering on the end crease where people will see after you are done painting.

product_title: Cool Baker Chocolate Treats Maker
review_headline: ... chance to try out this product and it was fun and easy
review_body: I had a chance to try out this product as a BzzAgent to give a review. It was fun and easy. My 6 years old daughter could do it all by herself and was very excited to do it and of course eat chocolate. Setup and process was not complicated at all. The most thing I like is melting the tray. Just put hot water in the melting tray (not too hot. I heated one cup of water in the microwave for a min.) Chocolate melted within 5 min. and just put chocolate into molds and put it in the freezer. But don't forget to put oil first because chocolate will stuck in molds(I failed at the first time so kids scooped up with a little spoon.) but with oil it worked well. And the instruction says to put chocolate in the freezer for 15 min. but it didn't hardened enough within 15 min. at least a few hours would be needed. Overall it was fun especially my daughter loved it and good to spend time with kids.

product_title: Air Hogs - Fury Jump Jet RC Helicopter
review_headline: I feel like Charlie Brown with the infamous "Kite-eating tree"
review_body:
I was SO EXCITED to get this! I thought it would be great fun, and I couldn't wait to try it! I wish I could write a more comprehensive review, but all I can do is relate my experience.

So here's what happened: It arrived, and I *immediately* opened it up and figured out what I had to do. I put the 4 AA batteries into the controller, and plugged in the helicopter to charge. A short while later, it was ready to go!

Even though the instructions said it could be flown indoors, I went outside (it's a nice day here, no wind). The Jump Jet took off beautifully! It went up in the air, I touched the "Transform" button to convert it to airplane mode, and it flew around the yard nicely! I had a little trouble controlling the altitude, though, and I was about to crash into the garden fence. I put it back into helicopter mode, and it went, hmmm, I guess "a little uncontrolled" is the best way to say it. Anyway, it rose up in the air, because I wanted to get it out of the crash zone (fence, basketball hoop, cars, house, etc.). Unfortunately, it didn't go straight up, it also went across the yard and near a tall locust tree (I swear, I was trying for straight up!). It hovered there a bit, maybe ten feet from the tree, about 70 feet up (it's a big tree). So then I tried to move it away from the tree. Oops. Into the tree it went! And STUCK there.

I flew it for all of about three minutes, and now it is stuck 60 feet up. I tried all the controls to get it free - and while it was still responding to the controls, I could not get it to shake itself free from the tree. So now I'm waiting for some good winds to blow it out of the tree.

Overall: the Jump Jet was easy to figure out and get started. Super-easy! Charging and getting started flying was a breeze - five stars for that! As for the flying, well, the controls are fairly intuitive and easy to use, but the helicopter mode is a touch unstable. Granted, I'm probably not the most talented pilot. (I refer the reader to my review of the Parrot Drone, which I crashed, repeatedly)

I would love to give this five stars, because it was three minutes of great fun! But all things considered, I'll just go with four stars based on the instability. If and when it comes down from the tree (hopefully uninjured from wind / rain / the fall) I'll try it again, and perhaps update my review. For now I'll just say, try it in a BIG open area until you get the hang of it. I thought my yard was big enough (since it is supposedly able to be flown INDOORS!?!?!???), but apparently not.

Good luck!

UPDATE: two and a half months later, this thing is STILL STUCK up in the tree! We even tried shooting it down with a potato cannon, but we weren't accurate enough. My hope for successful (and still functional) retrieval is waning. We shall see.. product_title: Magic The Gathering: Arena of the Planeswalkers Game
review_body:
Although I don’t have any experience with Magic, I do have extensive experience with Heroscape – Hasbro’s now discontinued game that has been re-born as this game.

For the most part the game is similar to Heroscape – the modular 3-d terrain for instance is identical to the pieces provided with the prior game. One major difference though is that while the entire board in Heroscape was created with modular 3-d tile, in Planeswalkers the majority of the board is a flat, cardboard hex map with a handful of the 3-D pieces added for elevation purposes. While not as impressive as the original game, the set-up/take-down of the new game is vastly better.

Planeswalkers also uses leaders and a hand of cards to enhance gameplay that differ from Heroscape. In general, I like both of these additions, though they don’t give as much flexibility in playing combinations of heroes as the original game (this may come with expansion in the future though).

The flow of the games is very comparable – move, use abilities, attack (if within range). Movement and line-of-Sight between elevations is also very similar.

In my plays so far it has been a fairly quick play – less than 30 minutes in a 2-player game. Combined with the quick set-up it makes this a good filler type game. I suspect it could slow down substantially with multiple players, though there is a very real danger of players ganging up on another and taking them out very quickly.

The only other missing component from Heroscape is that the miniatures were fully painted in that game – perhaps that is why that line was discontinued!

I can’t comment on the connection to Magic the Gathering – the inclusion of the hand of cards is certainly from that game and I assume that the heroes and other characters are directly out of that game also.

Overall, this game is just ok. Not the worst, but not the most interesting either.

product_title: Mindscope MSPUFOA Sky Lighter RC 9-Inch Drone, Red
review_headline: The charging cable is also easy to use/install as needed
review_body: This UFO is an enjoyable remote controlled toy!  It comes with a detailed set of instructions that make it clear to prepare the toy and use it for the first time (or repeated usage if you forget something!).  It comes pre-charged, but you will have to place two double A batteries in the remote (these are not included with the toy). The screwdriver that comes with the instructions is handy for removing the screw that holds the battery cover in place. The charging cable is also easy to use/install as needed, but again because it is pre-charged you won't need this right away.  The remote is easy to use and offers a variety of speed settings based on your pull - allowing for hovering mode or for you to send it soaring! It is easy to operate and has a great range (so you don't have to be right next to it/underneath it). It also appears to be very durable (I'm not very good at landing so it hit the ground quite a few times, rather hard, and you could not see any damage on it.  This would make a great birthday or Christmas gift for a child or an adult! It's fun for all ages!  I received this product as a sample from the seller in exchange for my honest evaluation and review.

product_title: Fisher-Price Bright Beats Smart Touch Play Space
review_headline: Unique look, but not a go-to for my 1yo.
review_body:
This "play space" bar is an OK toy but not a show stopper. The look of it is great, the sounds are subtle (vs. blaring like most kid toys), and it's easy to use. Its base is stable with regard to tipping, but it does slide on carpet. My husband said the assembly instructions were terrible and he ended up relying on the picture from the box! It took about 20 minutes total.
My 1yo likes to stand against it when doing other things like watching TV or playing with a toy in one hand. I haven't seen her engage in the music buttons/keys very much. In fact, she plays with the roller toys more than the sound part. The unit appears to have an auto-off feature, because we frequently have to turn it off and back on again so it will make sound. Good for saving those 4 C-batteries? Not sure, but it is a little frustrating to have to redo it a few times each day (especially since the switch isn't in the most convenient location). As of now, I'm lukewarm on it. It looks cool, she likes standing against it, but the playing part has been limited in the 2 weeks we've had it. If things change and she starts going crazy for it, I'll update!

product_title: Smash Up Game
review_headline: They "Smashed up" their rules and definitions for an added contradictory bonus!
review_body: This game can be fun if you have friends that like to nerd it out and argue over ambiguous definitions of words in the rules/on the cards, but it can be fairly confusing keeping track of which actions/abilities take effect at what time... for example, certain minions' ability say if they get "destroyed" then something happens, but the rules don't explicitly state what qualifies as "destroyed"- is it any time they go to the discard pile (per another card's action, or when a base scores), is it only when the action explicitly says "destroy this minion", or does it also include when they "go back into the owner's hand" per another action card/minion ability? It's fun to see how different pairs of decks mesh, but some overpower others, and different combinations of rules make some cards completely useless. Players who haven't played Smash Up before are in for some confusion the first couple rounds, but if you're not in it for competition but just to see what happens, it'll work out.

product_title: My Little Pony Poppin' Pinkie Pie Game
review_headline: Attractive, Fast, and Easy Game to Play
review_body:
Here is a toy that inspires mixed feelings. On the one hand, it can be addictive for short periods of time. On the other hand, the game is the same thing over and over. We played it and liked it. Winning is a matter of 100% chance.

Assembly is easy. Out of the box there are a few parts. One portion is the upper tier of a cake. Pinkie Pie is on a post that gets pushed into the lower tier of the cake. After Pinkie Pie is pushed into the upper tier, a lid covers Pinkie Pie. Lastly, there are twelve decorations. Each person inserts a decoration into the cake until Pinkie Pie pops out. The winner is the person who made Pinkie Pie pop out. Remove all the decorations, reset Pinkie Pie, and repeat.

On the plus side, this game is fast. From start to finish, the game is over in less than a minute. I doubt there are many children with an attention span of less than a minute. Resetting the game is relatively quick as well. If a couple of players are enthusiastic, they can keep track of the number of times each person wins. Also a plus, Pinkie Pie is the central character. If the game gets to be too boring, leave PInkie Pie popped up and keep the cake decorations on, and set the whole thing on a shelf as a decoration. What's to lose here?

On the down side, the game can get old quickly. On the other hand, you play for twenty minutes, get popping Pinkie Pie out of your system, and move on to another game. Some people might see the simplicity of the game as a downside, but in the 3-5 age range, simplicity is generally a good thing. However, even older children, all the way to grandparents, can find sufficient enjoyment in this game to make it worth playing for short periods (remember, a period is a non-zero duration of time).

This game is attractive, easy to play, and fast. It should be easy to explain to most children in the target age range, and even grandparents should find the game interesting for short periods.

Enjoy!

Enjoy!

The Syma Helicopter is very easy to fly! I was surprised at the fact I could keep it in the air without losing control or hitting a wall! I have mastered landing it on my Remote Control Helicopter Landing pad!

product_title: La Newborn Nursery 8 Piece Layette Baby Doll Gift Set
review_body: Our soon-to-be-2-year-old is also a soon-to-be-big-sister and loves babies, so we got this for her for her birthday.  We opened it up to check it out, but it's not quite her birthday yet, so she has yet to play with it.  Here are a few observations:  * The packaging is not frustration free. At all. * The size of a very small baby, yet it looks alert and it is somehow holding its head up--this doll has some features that are "preemie" and others that are 3-6 months.  That's fine, though--I can't think of any little kids that would hold these anachronisms against it. * My wife and I agree that the baby is very life-like without being too "creepy" (type "uncanny valley" into your favorite search engine). * All the pink implies this is a girl, but if you take the diaper off, it is genderless. * The overall weight and weight distribution seems about right for a human of that size. * The plastic is somewhat soft, though much harder than real skin would be. * There is a chemical smell from the plastic that I found unpleasant, but it is slight and I expect it will off-gas/disappear quickly.  I gave it to our 7 and 9 year old girls to play with for a while and they thought it was very cute and fun to pretend with.  I'm excited for our little one's birthday--I think she'll love it.  UPDATE Attached is a picture of our 2 day old, 8 pound (and a few ounces) baby next to the doll as a size comparison.  Also, it should be noted that the 2 year old likes the doll and I think it's a very good size for her.

product_title: Angeles Rest Angeles Germ-Free 2" Mat
review_headline: My girls love this mat, and I love the quality build.
review_body:
My Kindergartner loves her new nap mat. Most mats are only 5/8" thick and have a thin mil plastic covering. The thin mil plastic tears easily and generally has to be taped several times to get through the year. This one seems much more durable. We'll see if it can last the year, but from the feel of the plastic, if it doesn't last out the year nothing will.

I also love the extra thickness of this mat. I didn't want my little girl to feel like she was sleeping against the floor like you do with those 5/8" mats. The way the measuring works is if it says it is a 1" mat, it is actually only 5/8" of foam. If it advertises 2" like this one, you get 1-1/2" of foam thickness. That makes it pretty much like lumber measurements, so it's good to know before you buy.

While this will take up twice the storage space of the thinner mats, it is much higher quality and will provide better support and comfort for your child.

Hint, You can use a King-size pillow case to slip over the mat as a covering, and it is usually roomy enough to allow the child to use it as a sleeping bag.

product_title: LeapFrog PAW Patrol Imagicards Learning Game and Bonus Booster Pack
review_headline: I like almost everything about this game
review_body:
I like almost everything about this game. The activities are learning-oriented and work on more than just colors, shapes and the normal pre-school stuff.

Basically, you take a picture of a card with a pup, and that is your character in the game. You drive him around with your finger or the stylus and he finds people to help. When you tap the people that you help, they give you an activity that helps with learning shapes, numbers and colors. The nice thing is it also works on fine motor skills. For example, one of the games requires you to fill the fountain up with water. It's a counting game, but you also have to move the stylus in a circle. It also works on fine motor as you have to drive the pup around.

I wasn't a fan of the cards. I don't think my three-year-old gets them, and I think he would get frustrated. Luckily, they have a digital card picker, and you can use your stylus to choose the card you need for the game. I think this would have been a great game without cards to store.

Overall, it is a fun game, and my three-year-old enjoys it

product_title: My First Lab Mini Duo-Scope, MFL-20
review_body:
My First Lab has a well-known history for good microscopes, especially for kids, in a decent price range. This one is definitely a very beginner microscope and has a lot more of a toy feel than many other "first" microscopes" but is lighter and easier for a kid to move. it does have dual lights (above and below) that allow for easy viewing of slides - this user experience was that solid objects were not permeated by the light. It's battery powered, using 3 AAA batteries (not included). The eyepiece offers 10x magnification and the wheel allows for 40x, 100x, and 400x magnification. The eyepiece and tubing is smaller for littler eyes, but might prove a little problematic for bigger eyes that are helping the little ones focus.

I'm not sure how they get to 40 accessories, but it does come with:
• Brine Shrimp Eggs Specimen Vial
• 1 Yeast Specimen Vial
• 3 Empty Specimen Vials
• Graduated Cylinder
• 8 Blank Slides
• Hatchery
• Specimen Slicer
• Prepared Slides
• 8 Slide Labels & 8 Cover Slips
• Plastic Transfer Pipet
• Magnifying Glass
• Plastic Forceps

For very young kids, adults purchasing this will need to also purchase some additional slides for them to view. However, it's a decent microscope that will teach kids the basics of how to use one, and can provide a lot of cool opportunities for looking at the world in a very different way.

product_title: Wolfgang Pointer
Ideal Rage Card Game
review_headline: This game is great! I seriously enjoy playing this game
review_body:
This game is great! I seriously enjoy playing this game. But I HAVE to give it a 2 star rating because this particular generation of the game is almost unplayable. The difference between the orange and the yellow is extremely slight. I'm mildly colorblind, and I have to have the 0 for the yellow and orange side by side on the table just so I can identify the color of the cards in my hand. My spouse is not at all colorblind and she can barely tell the color difference. The red and green is also not noticeably different to a typical colorblind person, but I can tell the difference.

I have purchased 3 previous generations of this game, none of which have suffered from this problem. I really, really have no idea what the printers/designers were thinking making the colors so similar.

product_title: Tummple by BAXBO An Original Wooden Building Block Game (80 Piece Set)
review_headline: No more lost directions!  Box is strong and will withstand continued opening and closing. Lots of fun!
review_body:
Our family plays a lot of board games. We have one designated evening each week that is a mandatory family game night. No one is allowed to miss it. One of our favorite games is Jenga! When I saw the Baxbo Tummple, I decided I needed to see how it compared. It is so much better!!!

The first thing I noticed when opening was the quality of the box it is stored in. The box is very thick/heavy and holds all of the pieces perfectly. It also has the directions printed in the lid so there is no concerns of losing them. The instructions seemed minimal but once you play a few times you realize that they are as thorough as they need to be. The only issue I see that might arise in the future is what to do if there is a tie. There is no information provided for that scenario.

The game itself is simple. Rolling the dice will tell you which side you need to place the dice. Each time the structure falls, the person who made the blocks fall must put them in a pile in front of them. At the end of the game, the person with the most "negative points" (AKA- the most blocks), loses! My youngest son is our avid Jenga player. I will update once he plays this with us to let you know a child's perspective. His older brother and I played this several times to see what we thought of it as this will be a Christmas gift for the youngest.

I purchased this at a discount in exchange for an honest review of the product. I am selective in what I test and review and will always give an honest opinion.

review_headline: These dice are fantastic. I've used the Chessex brand of dice for ...
review_body:
These dice are fantastic. I've used the Chessex brand of dice for most of my years RPG'ing at the tabletop. The quality of Chessex dice is bar none and if you need to (as I did), you can simply call or email Chessex for a replacement die if you have a defective one. As the customer service response was immediate to a product defect, I still rate these five stars and recommend anyone to purchase game die for any game needs from Chessex.
In addition, you'll find that the sheer variety they have to offer is huge. Don't settle for white dice with black pips!!!

product_title: Nerf N-Strike Mega Series RotoFury Blaster
review_headline: Big Gun, Big Fun, But Not Quite "The One"
review_body:
I'm a big fan of Nerf toys, and was hoping for excellence here. It got close, but suffered a few flaws.

First of all, this thing launches Nerf mega darts like a champion, at least when it feeds properly. Range is phenomenal, and the whistling darts are hilarious. Each pump action rotates the cylinder and cocks it, just like a pump-action shotgun, though I was not able to hold the trigger down and continuously pump it to fire as fast as possible (not a big deal, just a fact).

Unfortunately, as I said, it suffers feed problems occasionally, and I've had darts jam in the barrel and muck the entire thing up. But when it's running solidly, it's incredibly fun. I had my daughter's 18-year-old boyfriend in a cringing in a corner and screaming like a baby. Big fun.

However, once you've exhausted your ammo and it's time to reload, you'd better find some good cover: it's a real pain to get the darts back in the chamber. It doesn't open, so you need to jam them into the exposed chambers and then rotate the cylinder to expose more. If you're in a Nerf-or-die situation, you'd better have someone covering your back or be carrying a backup Nerf, because you're going to be hurting.

When it's loaded and feeding smoothly though, it's a gas. And now my entire family is terrified. Awesome.

product_title: LeapFrog LeapTV Blaze and the Monster Machines Educational, Active Video Game
review_headline: Stunt Racing and STEM, a Great Combo!
review_body:
Young kids love driving games. There is something bout the thrill of doing something grown-up that has that appeal.

My five year-old twins thoroughly enjoy this game, and I secretly enjoy it because the girls are learning important STEM skills without even realizing it!

I also enjoy that there is a two player mode on the game, so that the girls can play together.

It is fun to see them experiment with cause and effect when constructing their Super Duper Stunt track, and they are motivated to keep playing so that they earn more track pieces.

This is a fun game, far beyond the recommended ages of 3-5. I predict a lot of re-play at our house!

Disclosure: We were given a copy of this game to facilitate my review. However, all opinions are my own.

product_title: Air Hogs Smash Bots - Remote Control Battling Robots
review_body: This package arrived just in time for my son's 11th Birthday and my 9 year old also enjoyed his big brother getting this gift.  I have broken down the following pro's and con's of the toys as I experienced them.  Pro's * The colors of the bots are bright and immediately attracted both of my boys to them * The "spinning" action of the toys has made my living room a fight to the death ring.  It is their favorite attack method * The controls are easy to learn * The additional weapons are interchangeable between the bots.  So each bot can have 1 blue and 1 yellow weapon which eliminated an almost argument about which weapon was "superior" and who got it!  (This was greatly appreciated) * The battery life has been longer than I had expected.  I spent a little extra and bought the extended life batteries so I am not sure if that made the difference but it was worth noting.  I haven't had to change the batteries since I put them in on August 24th and they have played with them every day.  Con's * The robots seem to have a cheap feel to them. (They have lasted a week's worth of play with no breakage but when I first opened the box the feel of the toys was disappointing) * They are small bots.  Not tiny but were smaller than what I expected when I saw the package online.  (I included two photos to show the packaging and then with the bots standing with the remote controls to try and show their size) * They require 10 AAA batteries to start with.  I only had AA batteries on hand so I had to make an emergency trip to town to get the much needed batteries * The additional weapons didn't really seem to make much impact on the "fighting".  They seemed to be just for decoration and didn't really offer an advantage to having them on. * They were very hard to get out of the packaging.  It took both me and my husband to get the robots out of the packaging.  Because they felt so fragile and cheap, we were afraid we would break them if we pulled too hard so it took some time to get them out.  Make sure to have your scissors handy! * My boy's biggest complaint was that the robots walked very slow.  The spinning action that they loved so much doesn't last very long so when that attack was no longer available they were unable to "run away".  Overall I gave this 4 stars because of the amount of batteries required and the difficulty I experience with the packaging as well.  Both of my boys have really enjoyed these bots and it is another way for them compete with each other.  Fifty dollars does seem quite pricy for this toy because I still believe the materials are a little cheap and I am unsure if they will still be functioning in a month or two; however, I was lucky enough to receive this item free in a BzzKit.  My BzzAgent name is jeleki.  I would recommend this product to anyone with boys who love robots and love to compete with each other and wants a toy that will be played with more than once.

review_body: This is one of the funniest games we've ever played. As big fans of Cards Against Humanity, we're definitely open to games that others may consider taboo due to strong language, irreverent themes and images, etc. If you're one of those people, but still want to check this game out, i highly recommend you order the "clean" version of this game instead. Regardless of which version you get, it's a lot of fun. It takes a little bit to figure out the rules, but once you get them, it's easy. It's a game of luck combined with strategy, and it's a ton of fun. We played with 3 and 4 people so far and I'm going to order another set so we can play with a larger group. Highly recommend!!!

product_title: Bunch O Balloons Water Balloons, 100 Balloons Per Minute
review_headline: Poor quality! Partially fills and deflates!
review_body: i ordered July 30 and received Sept 28.  The kids were SUPER excited!  The package came with 3 attachments, each having balloons and black rubber rings to hold them on already assembled.  No instructions.  The item is for one time use unless you buy a refill pack, which would be VERY time consuming to do.  However, that aside we were ready to have a blast. That feeling was short lived!  I attached the first one to the hose and only half the balloons would fill.  The others fell off with pretty much no water.  The biggest balloon got to about 2.5 inches big.  I thought ok maybe I did something wrong. As I was trying to put the non filled back on the spout, the 10-15 that did fill deflated water.  Imagine the disappointment of my 3 year old!!  We decided to give the second spout a try.  Same disappointment, only worse because I realized at this point my fun planned activity is a bust.  We threw the third out and started crafting!!!  Uugghh!  Don't waste your money!!!!

product_title: Magic The Gathering: Arena of the Planeswalkers Game
review_body:
This is a great value for what you're paying. Essentially, this game is based on another very good game called Heroscape. You'll build an arena out of the little pieces in this box, create an army, and do battle with one of the prepainted Planeswalker minis.

I picked this game up as a former MtG player. I was hugely involved in the game from Ice Age through Darksteel. I invested thousands of dollars in the game until it finally became apparent that I couldn't afford to continue to be competitive in the game. What I love about this is that there is a little of what I like about MtG - the deckbuilding, the spellcasting and the strategy - but not so much of what I don't like - the cost.

The game itself is solid if not spectacular. It accomodates up to 5 relatively seamlessly, and it's easy to set up the game as a 2 vs. 2 if you like the team approach, or to just make it a free-for-all. The biggest problem to me with the game, enough to lower it two full stars, is that the game feels like it is missing some essential element that will be added through expansions. It's difficult to identify exactly what it is, but I can't shake the feeling that they took something essential out and going to release it as a big box expansion in the next few months.

As it is, it's a solid game that feels unfinished. I'll eagerly look forward to the (I"m assuming) forthcoming expansion.

product_title: Ubongo - Sprint to Solve the Puzzle
review_body:
If you like speed-based puzzles, this game is for you. If you don't, you still might like it. This is not usually my cup of tea, but I really enjoyed playing this. You get a card with a blank space that needs to be filled with 3 (easy) or 4 (hard) Tetris-like pieces. You roll a custom die to pick which set of pieces you have to use and have a minute (sand-timer) to get the puzzle completed. (Each board has 6 possible sets of pieces that will complete it.)

You collect gems for being the first and second person to finish (up to 4 players), but all players who do complete theirs also get a draw a random gem from the bag. In this sense, there is quite a bit of randomness to the scoring, which serious gamers won't like. But you could tweak the rules a bit for that if you really wanted and just assign gems based on first-to-last. However, the randomness does help offset anyone from crushing everyone else by possibly sticking them with low-point gems.

The game is well-produced and the box insert fits everything perfectly. The weirdest part of the components is the bag, which is way too big for it's use. Yes, you're supposed to reach in and grab a gem, but the back could be half the size and anyone's hand could still fit in it. It's actually kind of annoying how big the gem bag is. But that doesn't affect the game play. It's straight forward and fun!

review_body: My toddler started watching Chuggington on tv and this was perfect for him to play with.  The very first thing I noticed about these Chuggington trains is that it is very securely packaged.  Each one was individually packaged and all 6 of them are separated by a piece of tissue paper in a box.  Each one has an id card with their picture, name, and number on it except for one.  It's okay if you misplace the cards or don't know all their names because the names are printed underneath each train.  They can all connect to one another.  There are 3 trains that have movable parts to keep the kids busy.  My toddler and his older siblings were able to play with these trains on the other brand train tracks we already have.  It works fine without a train track, as well.  They enjoyed playing with these Chuggington trains and asked if I can get more for them.  It's a great toy if they want more of it!  * I received this product at a discounted price in exchange for my honest review. *

product_title: Cool Baker Chocolate Treats Maker
review_body: I received this cool baker free to review as part of a BzzAgent campaign. My two girls, ages 6 and 8, could not wait to receive this cool baker in the mail. It was very easy for my 8 year old to put together by herself. It does not come with chocolate, but luckily I had a couple different kinds on hand. The instructions have you fill a three sectioned container with hot tap water in order to melt the chocolate. I was skeptical this would work, however, it melted the chocolate very easily. The only problem with this is that the sections are pretty small, so there is very little melted chocolate to work with at one time. We were, however, able to make 1-3 pieces of chocolate candy, depending on the molding size chosen, each time. This kit also comes with little gift bags and tags to put your creations in. I thought this was a great addition to the set. My girls have used this baking set several times and LOVED IT!! I thought the plastic parts were a little flimsy, but for the price I think it is a great gift for those little bakers in your life.

I took away a star because I used to equate the Melissa & Doug brand with high quality, safe toys, but the quality of this toy is so-so. Although the pieces don't seem like they'll fall apart, they feel flimsy and aren't well made. It also would've been nice if the shapes had a rattle or crinkly paper in them to add another dimension of play (the handle of the fishing rod has a cheap squeaker in it). product_title: Wild West Galloping Horse and Cowboy/Cowgirl Rider - Battery Operated Western Cowboy Horse Riding Toy for Kids (Exact Unit May Vary)
review_headline: which meant it was easy for a 3 year old to rip into
review_body:
The Wild West Galloping Horse from Lord Howard was a hit with my nephew!
It came simply packaged, which meant it was easy for a 3 year old to rip into.
It had very good instructions on the back as to how to "train" your Horse.
It also came with a battery so there was no having to wait to play!

The horse and cowboy unit are both well made. We did have some trouble getting the training wheel to work. The suction cup wouldn't stick to much. That was okay though because just watching the horse gallop was plenty enough fun for us.

The horse makes a very realistic "clomp, clomp" sound when it walks. It pretty much turns in one giant circle, so I think that it would be quite difficult to have an actual race with two horses. My nephew loved saying, "it's gonna crash!"

We truly had a ball watching this horse run. I received this product at a discount for my honest review.

product_title: Pokemon - Keldeo ex (45/113) - Legendary Treasures - Holo
review_body:
I opened and got this Keldeo EX card from a BW Boundaries Crossed booster pack. I was so glad to get this card because Keldeo is one of my favorite Water type Pokémon and one of my favorite Gen 5 Pokémon. The Legendary Trasures and Boundaries Crossed Keldeo EX card are the same card, but just a different set.

The drawing of Keldeo on this card is spectacular and beautiful, and the Pokémon EX cards are famous for their rarity and beautiful card art. It's attacks aren't all that great, but this card is worth finding and getting!

product_title: Oregon Scientific Dynamo 2 Activity Tracker PE289 Pink
review_headline: Unique wearable includes lots of features
review_body:
I have been fascinated with fitness trackers since they started becoming popular and I’m fortunate to say that I’ve been able to try many of them in the market. And today, I’m happy to bring you a review of a rather unique one from Oregon Scientific.
It’s very simply called the “Activity Tracker” and it’s got a lot of the same features that other fitness wearables do. So, I will just start with the basics. The Activity Tracker from Oregon Scientific comes in either pink or black rubber bands. It will track your movement through internal sensors and will analyze your sleeping wellness based off of how much you move during your sleep cycles. These are pretty standard options with fitness wearables. What is special about this Activity Tracker is that it will also track your heart rate and send notifications from your phone to your wrist. This function is typically something you only see on more advanced wearables and smart watches.

My first impressions of this device were generally good. It was comfortable and connected easily with my iPhone. It does require an app for connection, but that’s true of most fitness wearables. One thing I noticed right away was the digital display. A display is one of my ‘must haves’ with fitness wearables. This one shows activity and notifications. Plus it measures steps, calories burned, distance traveled, active minutes, inactive minutes and actual sleep time.

Unfortunately, I had some issues with the Activity Tracker functioning properly 100% of the time I was testing it. First of all, the battery seemed to drain unfashionably fast. The specs state that you should charge it at least once per week. I had to charge mine once a day. Also, the Activity Tracker is rated as water resistant up to 1 meter and it’s protected against accidental splashes, but I washed my hands at one point while I was testing it and after I dried it off, the tracker locked up and wouldn’t reset until the battery completely drained and I recharged it.

Based off of my experiences with Oregon Scientific’s products, I believe that my Activity Tracker may have been defective, but I felt that I needed to note these issues.

I did really enjoy the iOS app interface. It was very easy to read and the tracker synced flawlessly with my phone whenever the app was opened. It has very easy to read icons and a progress at-a-glance view. One thing I would have liked to see was an easier way to enter sleep mode. In order to enter sleep mode on this tracker, you have to open the app. There are many trackers that have similar option, but only require that you tap a button on the device to enable it. I’d love to see this option incorporated into future versions of this tracker.
You get a lot with this feature packed wearable. For a fraction of the cost of some of the fitness bands out there, you can do a lot more.

product_title: LeapFrog LeapTV Blaze and the Monster Machines Educational, Active Video Game
review_headline: This is a great racing game that is super easy for little kids
review_body: This is a great racing game that is super easy for little kids.  We have a Wii U and my older kids play MarioKart and the little kids are sad they can't play as well.  Once we got this game, they felt like they could do it and do it well!  This game is for slightly younger kids, so we were hoping this would work well for my 3 year old.  She still struggles to learn her letters and numbers, but I think these games are something that she will grow into and will reinforce concepts she learns at preschool which she starts in a few weeks.  This game was really easy and she played it fairly well.  You race the car on a track, avoiding obstacles and trying to collect 'golden tires'.  There are various questions that you have to answer that have to do with physics.  The words they use are a little advanced but once they play it several times, they get use to it.  Hopefully this will actually help them build vocabulary for when they learn physical science concepts in school.  Overall a very fun game!

product_title: MAGFORMERS Kit
review_headline: A toy that gets used after the first day
review_body:
Purchased these a couple weeks ago for my 6 1/2 year old son, and he loves them. Most toys get played with for a few minutes to an hour and then start collecting dust. So far he is playing with these every day, usually for well over an hour. He is having a lot of fun building all the items in the handout that comes with the set, as well as designing his own structures. With Lego's and other building toys he get very invested in keeping the items built intact and doesn't want to take apart and reuse the parts, with the Magformers he enjoys finding new ways to destroy the build and then see how fast he can recreate.

Great toy, will definitely get some more down the road.

review_body: This is fantastic! It's been a HUGE hit this summer. It's perfect for someone who wants a bouncy house and a water slide but doesn't want to take up a lot of space or put in a crazy amount of effort to store the thing. We actually leave it out on our lawn now and we'll put it away at the end of the summer. But it's very easy to fold up and put away. I'm 4'11' and i can put it away by myself without any help, once it's dry. Just let it dry for a few hours or even overnight and then put it away in a giant plastic bin from Lowe's or Home Depot. We put it on grass so didnt bother with a tarp underneath it and no pops or tears. 3 kids can jump comfortable in the bouncy part. I've had 2 sitting at the top of the slide, no problem and about 5 or 6 kids hanging out in the pool area. So you can really have about 10 kids playing on this thing at once. It's the best!! And when not using the water on the slide, it's still fun to use as a dry slide and bouncy so it's perfect all year round! I can even fit this in my basement in the winter months! it's the perfect size!

product_title: Morphun Jr Starter Rainbow 300 Piece Construction Mega Pack
review_body: I received a very nice set of Morphun junior blocks.  It came in a nice sturdy case/tub container so i didnt have to buy one!  It came in a set with 300 different pieces that included some square, triangle, wheels, and other pieces.  It had about 7 different colors.  It also included 5 double sided sheets of instructions for different patterns to build (animals, people, cars, etc.).  My son turned 4 in May so I got them out for us to build with.  I started with the hardest pattern to try (one of the bulldozers).  It took me a second to figure out how to get the pieces linked together.  It took my son a few tries to figure it out.  He still has some trouble. The box recommends it is for children ages 3+.  I don't know that he could have done it age 3.  He still can't follow the pattern yet.  I did help him with getting the pieces lined right and he was able to push them down.  I believe in time he will be able to do some of the easier patterns.  Overall they are great blocks.  He enjoyed just putting them together and making his own creation.  I would recommend them for any kids that like to build and out things together.  ** I did notice that sone patterns call for x number of pieces in a certain shape.  I wasn't able to find enough in the same color so we had to mix some of the colors.  You can see it in some of my pictures. It doesnt really bother me but did make it a ltitle harder for my son when he tried to match the colors in the picture.  I received this product at a discount in exchange for my honest and unbiased review.

product_title: Air Hogs - Fury Jump Jet RC Helicopter
review_body: Last year I had a different type of plane, a \\"Revell Control Fireshot.\\" I had my 2.5-year-old daughter trying to fly it, which resulted in several crashes. Finally I took the control away from her and promptly got the plane stuck high up in a large spruce tree. I believe it later blew out of the tree during a storm but went into a huge swampy area of shoulder-high crabgrass. It was a real bummer.    Anyway I was glad to get this plane as a replacement. It is in about the same class as far as weight, power, and price, but has the interesting vertical takeoff feature. I find that the vertical takeoff and in-flight switchover work just as claimed. I prefer this function over the so-called \\"multi-terrain\\" feature of the Revell, which was almost entirely advertising hype. Like the Revell, this Air Hogs model is totally helpless in even the slightest wind. Typically I find the plane is pointed back towards me yet keeps getting farther and farther away as it loses its fight against the breeze. I guess I can't expect any better from anything this small and light. If the wind blows it too far away, or too close to large buildings, or if it just climbs up too high to see clearly, I simply cut the throttle completely and it comes spiraling down. Then about 25 feet from impact I give it full power again and it pulls out of the dive, having reverted to helicopter mode automatically.    Battery life in the air seems acceptable, enough to get into trouble several times. Honestly the plane does not fly very fast and would probably get boring pretty soon if it did not get into some trouble. This plane charges off the remote control unit, which uses 4 AA batteries. Using Eneloop Ni-MH rechargeables, I found the plane charges up from dead out in about 35 minutes. Maybe it might charge a bit faster if you used the alkaline batteries the instructions recommend, as those have somewhat higher voltage. A little touch I really like is that the battery compartment in the control/charger doesnot need a screwdriver to open. There is a little button you can push in with the pointed bullet of a rifle cartridge, or with a pen point if you happen to have a pen.    The only thing I dislike about this plane is it seems to be very fragile. The wing appears pretty fragile, but I found with my Revell that this black material that looks like Styrofoam is actually many times tougher than Styrofoam would be, so I think now the wing is not the weakest part. It is the propellers that scare me most. The propeller shafts are extremely long and thin. There is some odd mechanism mounted to each propeller, almost like a variable pitch mechanism, which has some really tiny linkage parts. The propellers are also very exposed, and would hit the ground hard if you tried to land the plane without using the hover mode. There are also some exposed electrical wires that look pretty delicate. All I can say is, I think I will not be letting my daughter control this one. As another reviewer wrote, 14 years old would be a good age for flying this. Maybe 10 at the youngest. I'd take away more stars for this issue, except I did crash the plane a few times now and so far it did not break.    Under calm conditions this plane is great fun, and quite amazing in its function. I would just caution against putting $50 into this if the intended pilot is not a very mature and careful person.
