product_title: Schleich Farm Life Playmat Playset
review_headline: High Quality Horse Set Foundation Piece
review_body:
We're great fans of Schleich products - they are 'heirloom toys' quality meant to last several kids rather than the 'play and destroy' cheap toys so prevalent today. As well as hand details and care, expect a very nice product that you can that displays beautifully when not in use. So yes, very much worth the higher cost.

With the Playmat, we get the basis for a complete horse farm - from arena to stable. The mat is made in the EU (Germany) as are all Schleich products - so expect high standards for safety and quality. Although you might feel like this is a lure to invest in a complete set of Schleich horse products so you can fill in the sections, in truth you really don't need every piece. The playmat has a clean design that doesn't necessarily need all the buildings in order to be useful. But for horse loving kids, this really does set the stage for imaginative play.

The rug has a non skid backing and is made from easy care nylon. The edges have a quality finish that won't unravel. Ours laid flat easily once unrolled and our girls were ready to play.

We greatly enjoy our Schleich horses and sets and I enjoy having a toy that can be passed down to each child and then saved for grandchildren one day.

product_title: WowWee Robosapien Toy, Chrome/Silver
review_headline: More fun once you learn how to program the robot
review_body: Recently purchased this robot from Target's clearance for under 50 dollars. You can get bored very quickly if you just use it as a remote control toy since due to its analog nature, the robot can't even walk straight. However, the fun value of this robot increases significantly once you learn how to program it. The programming is very simple (using the included remote). The robot basically has three sensors: right touch sensor, left touch sensor and sound sensor and you basically program (maximum of 6 steps) the robot how to act when each sensor is activated. The cool thing is you can link up to 14 programs together so you can have a master program of up to 84 steps (14x6). I highly recommend the book "The Robosapien Companion" by James Samans if you want to learn more.

product_title: GoldieBlox, Benjamin's Cat Nook
review_headline: The basics of a type one lever
review_body:
As someone who understands the importance of getting girls interested in STEM, this is a good introduction to basic engineering with learning what a type one lever. But I'm a bit lost what's beyond the cute illustrations and simple lever.

You'll need some small nimbly fingers to get the pieces put together, my four year old daughter and husband were excited to see how everything went together and took about five to ten minutes to complete the build. The illustrations in the book are somewhat easy to follow, but we found some steps difficult without the added complete image as reference. The lever itself is neat and moves smoothly, the instruction book does go into small detail about the purpose of the build and a small story that gives background about the Benjamin cat and why he wants to be off the ground... However, since building it, my daughter is uninterested in it.

It is a good introduction to the GoldieBlox toys but I don't see myself purchasing this as gifts for friends. The pieces themselves are interchangeable with other GoldieBlox sets, but with the pieces alone, there aren't many options to create other things. It is however unique and colorful enough to interest anyone who enjoys building.

We were lucky to receive this product free of charge.

product_title: Air Hogs Smash Bots - Remote Control Battling Robots
review_headline: Fun to play, kids love it...but uses too much batteries
review_body:
I received this product as part of a promotion from the brand via BzzAgent.
In the package:
1x Blue Spinning "Smash Bot"
1x Blue remote control
1x Grey Spinning "Smash Bot"
1x Grey remote control
2x Lime Green weapon attachment
2x Light Blue weapon attachment
1x Cardboard Arena Mat
1x Set of instructions

The Good:
- (In my opinion) Cool & exciting concept: remote controlled spinning bots versus each other.
- Hard plastic, quality construction.
- Made by Air Hogs, quality brand name.
- Genuinely fun to play. My kids had a great time with them.
- Each bot comes with their own remote.
- Each remote and bot are paired together with their own individual channel, there are 3 channels per bot and remote so they radio frequency won't interfere with other bots and remotes.
- My kids loved that you could use the spinning mechanism on the remote control to make the bots spin faster.
- The remote control had two large buttons, which is great for kids.
- Screw in / out plates for battery compartments on both bots and remote control for safety.
- My kids were able to play it either on the floor (carpet) or on a table.

The Bad:
- Batteries...these are battery hogs! They take a combined total of 10 AAA batteries to operate. I had to go out and buy additional batteries just to make these work.
- Should of came with rechargeable batteries - With this product using 10 AAA batteries in mind, the cost to purchase rechargeable batteries outweighs the thought of purchasing these! Even if you were to get regular batteries, the cost to keep these running would be too expensive.
With 3 AAA batteries for each bot and an additional 2 AAA batteries for the remote, I expected them to last longer. They did last through 2 hours of ongoing play with my sons though, but you could see the bots spinning less and when they crashed, you could see it struggling to re-start spinning.
- The remote control is ok, but could be better designed ergonomically. It fits in my hands but my kids had a little trouble holding it for more than 10 minutes.
- The bots do no move forwards or backwards, they only spin. This made it really difficult when you had two bots separated and you wanted them to "clash" into each other. If you set them close enough to "clash", some times they would not have enough spinning force and they would simply get stuck together because both bots are spinning in separate directions. Maybe a forward or backward function in version 2?
- Bots were not customizable except with the included weapons.Maybe adding additional stickers could help out in the "customizing" department, my kids would of loved that.

Overall:
My kids genually loved these from the first day we received it and opened it. I had to run to the store for more batteries but after installation the bots were up and running.

My two boys had a lot of fun trying to knock the other bot over. I didn't even know about the "turbo" spinning button on the remote, my son figured it out on his own after an hour of playing with it.

In my opinion, this is truly a fun toy for my kids. They were laughing and enjoying the whole time they were playing it. Even when we took it over to their friend's houses or if other kids were coming over, everybody enjoyed them.

Unfortunately, the matter that it takes 10 AAA batteries to operate for just a couple of hours just takes away from the "parenting" aspect of maintaining this toy.I wished they included some kind of rechargeable battery system, even if they lasted for only 30 minutes of play. The "replay" value would of gone way up if they did include rechargeable batteries. I've had to re-purchase quite a few batteries already and AAA batteries aren't so cheap too.

Besides the battery issue, I would recommend these "Smash Bots'. They are fun and super challenging at the same time. The sturdy plastic construction and quality makes it an ideal toy because it's going to last for a long time, thus the 3 stars.

product_title: Thames & Kosmos Remote-Control Machines: Animals Science Kit
review_headline: Of the three "learning" type kits I've bought lately, this one was the best
review_body:
I was a bit hesitant with this. My son loves Legos, Mega Bloks, and building things like that. But we had tried a few "learning" type sets before, the notable failures were one that taught about alternative energy cars, the other that was not as bad as that was one that used rubber bands for power, letting you make a plane, a car, a boat... But each one I tried seemed better than the last, so I hoped my luck would hold out here, and the third would be the charm, or at least be better than what came before.

It doesn't come like the other building kits with a bunch of parts in a bag. Parts ARE in bags, but there's also a big slide out tray that everything is on inside the box, and that has a smaller four piece tray in it, that keeps things separated.

I was surprised at ultimately how few parts there are. This really does make for simple building of all the models. Everything is built around a central motor piece, the gears and such being placed around it in various ways depending on what you're building.

Things go together well, and the instructions for the mechanical side are very clear and concise. The "body" parts are a bit more tricky, but it specifies which are "mountain" and "valley" folds pretty clearly with different colors and patterns for the lines where the crease is on the pictures in the instruction book. And while I was a bit skeptical, they really did work out pretty well.

The mechanics are simple and easy for a kid to wrap their mind around. But my son's favorite was the orangutan (have to admit, that was my favorite too).

As another reviewer said, the replay value is limited, since once you've done one of them, successive builds don't really have as much of a thrill for them. The exception I found to this is when someone visits - family or his friends, he does enjoy building another time, being the "teacher' the second time around.

They're fun, and the price isn't bad considering how many animals you get to do here. It's a great way for young kids to see some simple engineering in work.fun, and the price isn't bad considering how many animals you get to do here. It's a great way for young kids to see some simple engineering in work.

product_title: Thames & Kosmos Remote-Control Machines: Animals Science Kit
review_body:
This is a fantastic kit for young minds, it allows for the exploration of the engineering of locomotion. The quadruped, biped and arm-over-arm methods are explored in this one kit. Essentially a simple robotics kit that allows for the remote controlled robot to be constructed in different forms to demonstrate the variations of locomotion.

It's an excellent kit and the construction method is similar to the old style advanced Lego kits. Anyone can manage this method of construction and, given that the kit only requires one motor and one remote, I expect that nearly anyone can manage to build all three bots and truly enjoy the exploration.

If you are one of those people that used to build simple mechanical bots in middle-school, then you might have a blast helping your kids explore the great kit... and the others.

This is a great educational toy that I can recommend very highly.

review_headline: Some slight issues, but they are beautiful!
review_body:
I like these, don't get me wrong.

First off, they are very big, and heavy. My arms are definitely going to be getting a work out with these poi. It makes them harder to swing at times as well. When watching people on youtube use these I assumed they were small, and light. Well we all know what happens when you assume! So the weight was unexpected.

The "pod" itself makes contact with the other poi happen very easily. So when your doing a butterfly, for instance, your going to hit at some point. For someone like me, that isn't very helpful :(

Taking them apart isn't very difficult, but it takes a bit of effort to pull them out of the pod. I thought I broke them at first when I tried, but the ring is supposed to come off.

All in all, these are good. The patterns are cool, and they look awesome at night. The recharging is wonderful, and so far battery life has been good. The ability to clean them is fine, but switching from the "crystal" poi's to these "pod" poi's was a change ;) Give them a try!

product_title: Nature Bound Binoculars Toy
review_body: Not the best toy binoculars in the world, but they work well for a 3 years old.  I ordered these Nature Bound Toy Binoculars for my 3 year old grandson after I purchased a pair of better, more expensive ones for his 6 year old brother.  These binoculars made him happy and worked well enough to make him feel like he was using "real" binoculars like his brother!  The best part about these Nature Bound Binoculars is that they are really sturdy!!!  They've taken a lot of falls without breaking, cracking or coming apart.  My little guy doesn't quite get the concept of being able to "see" distant things (like birds or baseball outfielders) but  he really enjoys looking at "giant" people and objects when he focuses on things that are relatively close.  All in all, I'm pleased with how sturdy these are and how well they work for a 3 year old!

product_title: DIY PBN-paint by number famous painting Spring House by Thomas Kinkade 16X20 inches Frameless.
review_headline: and it goes on smooth & looks fine.
review_body: This comes in the mail in a small box with the fabric canvas folded, paints, brushes, number guide, and a tiny 3 1/4" x  4 1/4" picture of completed product. The canvas appears to be possibly a type of vinyl laminated to an even weave fabric. It comes folded up & the folds are creased into the fabric. It has to be stretched to eliminate the folds, which involves purchasing something to stretch it with. I used a frame  meant for working cross stitch or needlepoint, which meant rolling it onto the bars & having to roll it several times to put the creases in the center & roll & lock tight, then turn it sideways & repeat process. All but the center crease came out this way & that is more of a roll in the fabric now than a crease. So I am going to try putting it back on the frame again for a longer period of time. I left it on for each crease for 1 day. This is timely & I'm sure there is something out there that is meant for stretching fabric. Possibly a quilting product? I did paint a small area to see how the paint went onto this type of canvas, and it goes on smooth & looks fine.

product_title: High Speed Puzzle Cube (Tanbi Puzzles RC100) 3x3 Stickerless (3 By 3) Magic
review_body: This cube is decent, but it doesn't spin as freely as some others. The build is quality, and stickerless is always a perk. It has yellow opposite white, which is my preference. It has never jammed up on me, which is great. When I opened mine it had a light coating of oily residue on it, so I assume it came pre-lubricated. As far as speed cubes go, though, it turns a bit slowly. Much better than say, Rubik's, but my Dayan II Guhong spins circles around this thing. Adjusting the tension is very easy on this cube, as well. Each center cube has a panel on it with a screw under it and the panels pop off easily without disassembling the whole cube. Though it doesn't spin as freely as my Dayan, it spins loosely, if that makes sense. It doesn't take much force to spin it, but it turns in a controlled manner, so I use both cubes at different times for different reasons. I received a discount on this item for review purposes; all review content is my own and not influenced by the discount or seller in any way.

product_title: Friday board game
review_body:
I've played through this several times now, and enjoy it a lot. The choices of when to spend life, when to destroy cards, and how to deal with the various hazards and pirates give you a lot of strategic options in a relatively simple rule set.
The art on the cards is great, very amusing and evocative of whatever the card's describing, and they handle easily while also not taking up too much space. They're like small Tarot cards: much taller than they are wide. Cards are of good quality, thick and with nice printing.
The life tokens are painted wood Eurogame-style pieces, very cool and different from the generic designs found in other games. They come in a resealable bag.
The three mini-boards/tiles for the different stacks of cards are nicely printed and have a bit of reference material on them, as well.
This game gets extra points for having a rather small box, minimal instructions, and components that can be easily and quickly put back in the box. The 'mini-boards' concept works a lot better and lasts a lot longer than a quad-folding board.
Overall, great solo game. Fun to play and fun to watch others play. Robinson has a lot of character, and the multiple challenge levels and scoring system add even more replayability to this. It's worth checking out!

product_title: Kurio Xtreme Tablet
review_body:
There are so many great tablets built with an Intel® Atom™ based processor, including the Kurio Xtreme tablet for kids. I got to check out the Kurio Xtreme with my family and it has been a hit. Even my husband has used it, and he usually avoids kids "toys." Well the Kurio Xtreme is not a toy, it is a beast of a tablet thanks to the Intel® Atom™ based processor. It loads up right away and downloads apps before I realize it. Speed is not the only thing that I like about the Kurio Xtreme, there are lots of great features on it.
Features I like on the Kurio Xtreme:

Comes pre-loaded with more than 90 apps including popular games like Fruit Ninja, Subway Surfer and Cut the Rope 2. You get access to over 150 e-books as well.

Kurio Genius parental controls. You can set up different profiles for your kids and decide their internet access, apps they can play and times they can play on the device. This is awesome because as a busy mom I don't have time to sit and monitor what each child is doing on their tablets or if I'm not with them I don't have to worry. My kids bring their tablets to friends houses and their grandparents and with Kurio Xtreme Parental Controls and Profiles, its like I am watching over them.

Going along with Parental Controls, Kurio has the Kurio Genius Internet Filtering System. This filters, categorizes and updates 450+ million websites daily to make sure kids are staying safe online and not viewing anything they are not supposed to. Parents can set the strictness of controls and lessen controls as kids grow.

7-inch touch screen with 5-point multi-touch. Let's face it, kids want to touch screens, its being the norm now that even with our non-touch screen computer they try to touch the screen. We haven't had any issues with the touch screen.

Android Operating System - This is great because not only do you get the Google Play Store but also the Amazon App Store. Kurio also has their own app store you can get kid-friendly apps from.

Create up to 8 profiles, perfect for everyone in the family. Yes this is not just a kids tablet, I can log in onto my profile and check my email, play a game, surf the web or go on my social networks. Then when I am done, I log out and my kids can log into their own profiles and just access what I allow them to.

1st tablet with Body Motion Gaming! This is seriously awesome. My whole family has done this and it is a great way to unwind. We just prop on the kitchen counter with the included stand and pick a game under Motion Sport such as skiing, soccer, swimming or running and we start moving. A picture of you pops up on the bottom right and you have to move to make your character move on the screen. The faster you move, the faster your player will move! Its funny to see us working up a sweat playing a game in the kitchen!

Includes protective bumper. I appreciate when tablets come with a case because it is one less thing I need to buy and I can let my kids use it right out of the box without worrying.

Categorize games for profiles. you can categorize where the games fit. The categories include Games, Educational, Media, Ebooks and more. You can then go a step further and choose which categories are subject to time management. For example, lets say you are fine with your child reading Ebooks all day or anything in the Educational category but for the Games category you want it limited to certain hours of the day - well you can do that!

What I wish it had:

I do wish it was a little bit bigger but 7 inches is a decent size.

It would be nice too if there was a stand that popped out from the back rather than came separate so we don't have to prop it when we don't have the stand with us.

More Body Motion games.

Overall, I really like the features of the Kurio Xtreme. It makes it really easy to manage my kids on it and we allhave fun using it. For the price of just over $100, I'd say its a good value and it can be a tablet that grows with your child or one that all your child share (if thats possible) with their own profiles. There is so much that can be customized on this tablet from the profile screens to what games the categories go in. I feel like we haven't even scratched the surface of what this tablet will do, especially because one of my three kids is usually on it so I don't get much play time on it.

I received this product complimentary in exchange for sharing my honest opinion.have fun using it. product_title: VTech Go! Go! Smart Wheels Ultimate RC Speedway
review_headline: I'm a big fan of the Smart Wheels but this needs to be fixed
review_body:
[[VIDEOID:484dea32ddcb0bfc2030d37d500c4120]]We already own several Smart Wheels play sets. The video shows this Smart Wheels set combined with parts of 3 or 4 other Smart Wheels sets. In total we own about 7-8 different Smart Wheels sets.

[Good]

The Smart Wheels design team is very ambitious. The new features are exciting. The best one is the remote controlled car. Yes it only goes back and forth, but that's all you need. My child loves this feature and he can barely talk. It's an awesome idea.

The idea of having smart vehicles that talk and light up depending on the tracks indentation is really ingenious. This adds to the fun and education.

The play set is somewhat interactive. It has lights and sounds, and the track triggers the Smart Wheels cars to start talking which is always cool.

The environment is even more interactive with the car itself? What does this mean? Now in addition to making the cars talk while moving over tracks, when the car is moving using its own motor there's gears it can hit that activates an elevator, moving the car up 3 levels. There's even a cool pit stop that activates a bunch of gears like clock work. More on this in the 'Bad' section. There's even a really cool bridge (unlike the others this one is perfect in execution) as well as two track diverters (another cool idea).

It has some educational value. Like the Smart Wheels garage, it sings learning songs and talks.

There is a lot of creativity involved and even problem solving. It takes planing to be able to complete the construction of a Smart Wheels track, given what pieces you have and how much space is available to build it in. Smart Wheels is basically Legos for cars, with the roads being the basic building blocks.

You can take apart the play sets and store them.

[Ok]

While remote controlled car motor is stronger than the Smart Wheels train motor, it's still too weak to move through a few existing Smart Wheels tracks that aren't included in this set. This is a minor complaint and just a nice to have in the future feature.

[Bad]

Buggy interactive tracks: The only new movement reacting tracks that work every time is the red bridge and the track diverters. Unfortunately both the pit stop and the elevator ramp track are both victims of either poor design or manufacturing defects. With the pit stop, the gears don't always activate and the car gets stuck there. With the elevator, it only worked twice. Every other time after, the car just shoots forward off of the elevator, making it useless. Based on other reviews, it seems like VTech either didn't properly test these features or they just didn't care and just decided to ship them out. I'm not sure which scenario is more disturbing.

There is a lot of trial and error when setting up Smart Wheels tracks for motorized Smart Wheels cars as opposed to Smart Wheels cars being moved manually. Many times unless the tracks are just right, the remote controlled car will get stuck or go off the track on sharp curves and so on.

Smart Wheels needs space, though you could always take them apart after play.

This is one of the more expensive Smart Wheels sets, which is bad since unlike the other Smart Wheels play sets; major pieces don't work.

[Verdict]

I would try to purchase the draw bridge and the remote control car separately instead. However if you're a big fan you really don't have much of a choice but to buy this set even with the flaws (the moving bridge is totally worth it even though two major tracks don't work). If you're not really familiar with Smart Wheels, I would start out with one of there other sets instead like the Train set: [[ASIN:B00DKCI1P6 VTech Go! Go! Smart Wheels Train Station Playset]]

I really wanted to rate this higher, but this just needs to be fixed.

product_title: Folkmanis Skunk Hand Puppet
review_body:
This is so CUUUTE!! As someone who has attended Skunk festivals (real live skunks, de-scented, people's legal pets), I thought I'd bring this to work to playfully show to my coworkers, one of whom recently wrote up my bio in the office paper -- which included my Skunk festival attendances. Well everyone loved it-- but it scared the %^# out of one person-- we almost had to get the smelling salts, After apologizing profusely, I realized this skunkie was much more realistic than I expected. I was able to get my hand into it and wiggle its paws, move its mouth ad turn its head -- and there IS a hole under the tail for one finger to move the tail around, but that's a bit awkward.
Only problem I had was the interior finish-- some of the seams are scratchy -- I had to get my little Swiss Army Knife scissors and veery caarefully trim some of the hard edges.
No, I do not own a skunk as a pet-- I don't live in a Skunks Legal state. Therefore I have Skunk Envy. This little rapscallion fills the need.

[[VIDEOID:88d579c8a238c14f5bb8c50b1eb35e32]]What a cute little car, this is quite the little car.This is something any child would be thrilled to have .

The players are supposed to have the same set of tiles in the game, but our set had two different sets, which made one player at clear disadvantage. The box is oversized for the game, and you can actually fit the game with the orange tokens up and still be able to close the lid - good for taking a break, but not very necessary since the game play is very short.

product_title: Monster High Doll Gore-geous Ghoul Beast Freaky Friend 28 Voltageous Ghoul Friend
review_headline: Great Idea, But A Bit Flawed....
review_body: I like this doll a lot. She's a lot like the Inner Monsters a line I really went crazy over and the idea of a 28" Inner Monster was just too tempting for me. I had to spring for her. She was a bit expensive but then again she's 28" tall and that's a lot of plastic. I think she's very pretty but she has a couple of fatal flaws that I'm not happy about given her hefty price. There is NO articulation on her knees. The joints there are fake and given that price tag she should have real knee joints. This is ridiculous. She does have arm and wrist articulation though. Her shoes do not come off without considerable force because there are dots of glue holding them and her feet don't even look like proper feet which is going to making giving any other shoes very difficult. If you don't mind one dress, one pair of shoes, that's okay, but I was really hoping to find other stuff in my collection that might fit her feet and I don't think that's going to work well.  She doesn't seem to have a theme per se. She's got a bunch of accessories that look like they could belong to several different kinds of monster. She's got were ears, but flippers, gargoyle wings and vines like Venus. It's like she's several different characters in one doll. It's a little weird. If it had not been for the non-articulated knees I'd have probably lived with the rest but the knee thing, it really sucks...

product_title: Fisher Price Disney Minnie - Fabulous Minnie Mall
review_body:
One of the things I really liked about this playset is that you can separate it into two locations, or keep it together. If your kids just want to play with one part of it, they can! Assembly only takes a couple of minutes, and the car is ready to go right out of the box. Everything is colorful, there's a lot to do, you get a couple of cute figures, and everything that moves doesn't require batteries or constant cranking in order to operate. You have escalators, a slide, a merry-go-round, and a bunch of shopping-related things to play with.

The main drawbacks to the set are that a lot of things here just don't work like they should. Some pieces are too big or small for where they go, and a couple of the parts are on the flimsy side. The slide and escalator in particular. They work...just not very well. Because things aren't balanced, a lot of times, the figures will fall out of place when something is moving. It can get very frustrating for kids fast. If this were a cheaper playset, it wouldn't be such a downer, but you're paying half a Benjamin on this thing. There's no real way to fix any of this either.

review_headline: easily, and freely as Lego pieces
review_body: While the finished product is spectacular, Mega Bloks has a long way to go in order to make them a serious contender in the building-block industry. The pieces do not connect as readily, easily, and freely as Lego pieces, and the packaging is the worst part. While the sets arrive in several separate sealed plastic bags, they are not numbered (like Lego) and seem to have no rhyme or reason of separation. Because of this packages, the instructions cannot direct a child to numbered bags for specific parts needed throughout the process of building.

product_title: VTech Activity Cube
review_headline: Baby Loves it, It drives Mommy to drink....
review_body:
So I'll preface this review by saying my young child loves this. As a parent it drives me crazy for two main reasons:

1) The sound doesn't stop when the baby stops playing with it! It shuts off eventually, but baby can stop pressing the buttons and it still makes noise for a bit.

2) I'd admit this is petty, but it drives me NUTS that the song this cube sings has the words: "There's fun on five sides... the cube is fun for everyone!" The cube has six sides, not five! And yes, I understand that one side is pretty boring and that's why the song says that, but for the love of every math geek in the country, please change the song so my kid doesn't grow up thinking a cube has five sides! Like I said, I know it's petty, but by the 400th time it really gets on your nerves...

product_title: Magformers Inspire Set (14-pieces)
review_headline: Great Toys - Shame About the  Gendered Marketing
review_body:
Magformers are fantastic toys for boys and girls. My 4 year old granddaughter has enjoyed playing with them for a year already and they remain one of her favorite toys - a couple of days ago she made a playground, complete with Ferris Wheel.

Marketing this one tiny set in pastel colors to girls really distresses me. It's made worse by the fact that this seem to be the only set in these colors. It's a pale imitation of what the bigger sets provide. Do yourself a favor and buy a bigger set in regular colors so the building options are much greater. The ones in the $40 range have enough pieces to really exercise the imagination. Your girls (and boys) will get much from it.

One of the advantages of Magformers for Moms and Dads is that because the pieces are magnetic they store compactly and there are no little pieces underfoot, as there are with other building sets.

He was 3 when we got it for him so he was never really interested in the rocking part of it but we have had it now over a year and he still loves it!! We got the yellow and blue which was significantly cheaper at the time (not sure why) but happy with it!! 100% recommend

product_title: The Learning Journey Techno Gears Marble Mania Zoomerang Building Kit
review_body:
My adult son spent his entire childhood playing with toys like this, from Legos and Lincoln Logs to Erector sets and, finally, his favorite - complex roller coasters. Now, he's a structural engineer who designs skyscrapers - but how does he like to relax when he comes home? Building these things. Oh, ostensibly, he builds them with his five-year-old son, but he's been doing this since the boy was an infant. My grandson appears to be a chip off his father, but at five, he's far too young to assemble this toy on his own, even though it says "six and up." (Normally he is a couple years ahead of the curve on any building toy.)

Building this marble maze was a lot of fun - for my son. He had it together in less than an hour, but it was fairly painstaking. Things have to line up perfectly, the black connectors must be turned the same way, etc. My grandson helped a little but kept getting bored. Just like me.

Once the set was complete, adult and the child both had a great time. Only three marbles come with the set - they added more immediately. It reminds me of a Rube Goldberg contraption - it's very amusing. Sometimes the marbles jump the track and the gears can be a little clunky if you stop turning them at the wrong moment.

This maze is probably best for very patient kids above the age of eight or ten who really enjoy building. A twelve-year-old would love it - as do adult kids. I'd give it four stars for my son and three for my grandson because he does love playing with it now that it's built.

review_headline: Get Glenn before Glenn gets got!

He is very detailed and if you are a comic book fan you do know his days are numbered so grab him now before his demise, if you wait until then the price will be so much more. Bottom line : if you are thinking about collecting TWD figures, start here.
Great quality, shipped fast and fantastic price.

product_title: Model Factory-Hiro Aston Martin DP 214 1/24 Scale Full Detail Model Kit
review_headline: This is an heirloom - it should not be considered a toy.
review_body:
The 1:24 Aston-Martin DP 214 by Model Factory HIRO is exactly what you would when bringing two of the world's premier marquee's together - unquestionable excellence.

Make no mistake; this is not a toy that can be slapped together in an afternoon or two. It becomes, when given time and talent, a family heirloom - one that will proudly passed to future generations. Building experience, aptitude, dry fits, good painting techniques, etc, will all come into play during the building kit. It is robust and will not deteriorate and be spirited away into a rarely used closet, but hold a place of dignity and pride within a decor.

Unlike the age group suggested by MFH, I would personally suggest an age of 18 to 20 years before taking on such an undertaking.

With best regards, Wolf

product_title: Turnigy Accucel-6 50W 6A Balancer Charger LiPo LiFe NiMh NiCd JST-XH w/ MANUAL!
review_body:
Its a great little charger. I just got into quadcopters and this charger had the features I wanted, and its been performing well for me. My batteries have XT60 connectors so the included connectors are charging them nicely. It charges very fast and while I'm sure there's fancier chargers out there, this one suits me fine. It supports every battery I need and it has a lot of options for charging output, and you can save customized charging settings for each battery you have, which is a nice feature.

This charger does come with a cable that has a plug for the input to the charger on one end, and aligator clips on the other, but it does not have an AC adapter included. You could either buy an adapter and hope it includes the proper connector, plug it into a 12v battery terminal, or do what i did: I found an old 12v 2a adapter for a router i dont use anymore, I cut the wires and stripped away a small lead and clipped on the included aligator clips and powered the unit like that. Its working great so far.

product_title: Cool Baker Chocolate Treats Maker
review_headline: A fun family activity, if everyone has patience
review_body:
I received this product as part of a BzzAgent review. My two daughters (10 and 6) were very excited to try out the chocolate maker, as they had seen this in stores earlier in the summer. Assembly was very easy and quick. Only five pieces needed to be snapped into place and then we were ready to start melting chocolate. The product advertises that no microwave needed, but I was very hesitant about how the melting process would work. According to the product instructions, simply fill the melting container with hot tap water, screw on the top, and then place chocolate chips or pieces into the bowl. There is a divider for keeping different color chocolates separate. To be honest, after reading the directions, this was the step I was most concerned about. On my first attempt, I filled the container with hot tap water, placed the chocolate, and waited the instructed 2 minutes before stirring. It did not go well. The pieces were still completely solid, and while we did manage to start breaking up the pieces with the included plastic spatula, the process took a long time. Plus, there was little room to operate with the divider inserted. We abandoned the stirring process and elected to melt our chocolate in the microwave. We did pour the melted chocolate back into the melting container as we began the decorating process, though. While the included container might not melt the chocolate at a speed satisfactory for kids, it did an excellent job of keeping the chocolate heated and workable.

The decorating process was a bit tedious for the children, but they had a very good time trying to add color to the owl and chocolate square molds. While we won't win artistic awards, both girls were pleased with the resulting appearance. I had a little more luck with the chocolate pops mold, but the cupcake and swirl patterns were much smaller and tedious. I did lose some of the chocolate decoration on both the swirl and the cupcake mold when I popped them out of the freezer, but I may not have added enough cooking spray to the molds at the start. The spinner was a neat feature for the girls to operate, but both were more interested in popping their molds into the freezer than in completing the process of spinning the chocolate to ensure it is well coated and dispersed within the molds.

Overall, the product was fun, and I'm sure my daughters will get some continued use out of it, much like their Easy-Bake Oven. We haven't yet prepared chocolates to package with the included wraps and decorations, but I expect that to be a weekend project soon. The product is all plastic, and, while the gyroscope spinner seems well built, the two "legs" don't seem to be very solid, so the spinning process may wear on them, especially with an "enthusiastic" child on the handle. Clean up was very easy.

Pros: Easy assembly, cute molds.
Cons: Chocolate is not included, melting process takes a while.

product_title: Leray Self Balancing Scooter Balance Motion 6.5" Two Wheel Hoverboard with Certified Safe Battery Pack (Black)
review_headline: The Leray Dreamwalker is the ultimate in cool, high-quality, but not intuitive to ride ...
review_body:
[[VIDEOID:c3022c076c09ab44153cf1e1de508fc5]]The Dreamwalker obviously isn't for anyone, including children, those under 5' tall, and 220 pounds on up. Perhaps I could exclude myself on the grounds that I don't have that innate finely honed balance that one should have before attempting to ride. Some people are naturals and can skate board, snow board, ski or use a self-balancing scooter with ease. This is certainly not a toy and although many find it easy to use with little challenges, others I know who've tried have taken potentially serious spills. Take a pass if you don't have the coordination to manage the Dreamwalker.

I've had the Dreamwalker for a couple of weeks now and people shy away from it like it had the plague. It's a totally solid piece of machinery and I've had zero problems with the battery. I've been testing it on and off, when no one's looking of course, and really like it. I rather draw the line at the word \\"love,\\" but as far as the technology and the quality of this self-balancing scooter, it's top-notch. I wouldn't go so far as to say that learning how to ride is intuitive because it's not. People do rave about how easy it is, but that \\"easy\\" comes with practice and allowing the body to relax and guide the Dreamwalker.

First up, getting on (and subsequently off) the scooter is the critical part. The way to mount the Dreamwalker's platform is to quickly put your strongest foot up first very quickly followed by your other one. It's rather like a quick hop. Getting off the scooter is just the reverse. Quickly dismount to the rear with you weakest foot first and then your strong one. If you have a hallway where you can move freely up and down, that would be the perfect practice field so to speak. Seriously don't believe these people who pick it up in five minutes and are off.

I had problems initially because I was not letting my body do the work, but I was trying to insist the scooter do what I wanted. The key, for me anyway, was to relax and not overthink the task at hand. You still won't see me traveling to the local store in back anytime soon, but I am quickly gaining a decent amount of control. Not to discourage anyone, but I just want to be more realistic. This is great fun, but not intuitive. Oh, and I had a rock climbing helmet on and I suggest that anyone who uses one put on the protective gear. The first few attempts at getting on and off the Dreamwalker just could throw you on your back.

The Dreamwalker has a lithium ion battery, which is the ultimate in dependable. When I want to charge it's simply an overnight deal. It does come fully charged, but instead of waiting with bated breath, the overnight makes like simple. The body of the Dreamwalker appears to be an impact-resistant polyurethane, but obviously not scratch-resistant. Until you get really good at working with this self-balancing scooter, you can easily put your own bumpers on. I'm not really worried about scuffing (it will happen) try putting some self-adhesive weather seal on until you are good at it. It's rather like putting training wheels on a bicycle.

There are seriously no problems with the Dreamwalker, but the problems are with the user. I need to learn to relax more instead of trying to think for the scooter. What is does is pick up on my subtle muscle movements. When I first tried it out, it seemed as if my body were resisting and the scooter decided I wanted to go backwards each time. As I mentioned, a hallway would be a great practice field. The hands can lightly guide and give some confidence. I was all over the place for a while, but fortunately I didn't fall. The Dreamwalker is the ultimate in cool, high-quality, but not intuitive. Would I recommend it? If you are capable, yes, but it you can't walk and chew gum, take a pass.

product_title: uxcell 12VDC 20A Two Position ON/OFF SPST 0.47" Mount Blue Light Toggle Switch 10 Pcs
review_headline: Illumination is in the base, not in the toggle handle
review_body:
The light is an incadescent bulb in the rectangular base of the switch, the toggle (handle) is not illuminated. As others mentioned, when mounted, the light will be invisible unless the installation will accomodate an opening in the backing material so the bulb can remain visible.

Regarding the switch resistance, it is close to 0 ohms between power (+) and ACC, that is what needs to be hooked up for switching. People measuring 25 ohm are doing so between power (+) and ground (-), which is the resistance of the lamp filament. If you want the light to work, connect your circuit + to power (+), your circuit ground to ground, and your switched lead to ACC. If you don't need the lamp, then connect your + to power (+) and your switched lead to ACC.

Only 3 stars from me for not making the description clear about the nature of the illumination - I was also erroneously expecting the toggle handle to light up.

product_title: Holy Stone X300C FPV RC Quadcopter Drone with Wifi Camera 2.4G 4CH 6-Axis Gyro RTF Headless Mode
review_headline: Fun to fly, but very limited lifetime
review_body:
I was attracted to this as my first drone, thinking that the video-over-wifi would be a cheap way to get pseudo-FPV. On my first day playing with it, I got it stuck high up in a tree, where it stayed for two weeks until I could get some long enough bamboo canes (40'+). It survived the weather for those two weeks, and has survived a regular number of knocks and collisions since, but I've had to use hot glue and reinforcements to repair it on a regular basis. However, it's now on its last legs, with flight time of only around a dozen hours.

Durability is a serious issue; all beginners are going to crash while learning to fly line of sight, and it's unfortunate that the build quality isn't tougher. The crash guard is made from thin plastic, which breaks on almost any hard hit where it meets the legs of the drone. Hot glue does a decent job at repairing it, but the joints should be far tougher, and probably the material improved. (By the way, the crash guard makes it far more likely to get stuck in trees, so it is a mixed blessing.) After a collision, one of the drone legs snapped (they're made from a hollow and brittle plastic shell); I reinforced it by putting a nail inside the leg and another nail outside, and pouring on plenty of hot glue, in a kind of makeshift splint -- that worked well enough, and has held up. The real nail in the coffin, though, is that the threads on one axle that the propeller screw attaches to have stripped after taking the prop on and off only 3-4 times (I was trying to figure out why the prop wasn't providing lift, eventually realizing that I was using the wrong prop -- the two reds are actually opposite shapes, and you need to replace like for like.) So, the prop is now glued to the axle, since the screw is useless, which means that the drone is on borrowed time.

I could never get the wifi to work. Holy Stone support have been very good; they sent me photos of the interior where the wifi board plugs into the main board -- their theory is that the plug got loose after a crash. However, since the leg is glued up I can't get at the internals. I half thought about using a dremel to cut into it, but that's more time than I want to put into it right now.

It's quite fun to fly, and responsive. The batteries give a reasonable flight time, and it's nice that they provide two batteries.

In short, a reasonable choice to learn with; just exercise some caution while learning.

product_title: 3 Inflatable SHARKS/Shark INFLATES/Party DECORATIONS/DECOR/FAVORS 24"
review_headline: Perfect as party decor. Durable beyond party use
review_body: Very cute decoration for Son's 7th birthday party!  As soon as I saw them here on Amazon, I knew they would be an ideal decoration for upcoming shark-themed birthday party this past June, but was hesitant at first since I read another review that claimed these were a bit delicate.I'm so glad I ended up purchasing shark inflatables as they were too cute, with tons of compliments, and as for being easily damaged, our experience has demonstrated these are anything but decorations only!  Once we had these blown up a day or so before Son's  party, he and his rambunctious 4-year-old sister  just couldn't seem to stay away from the sharks, even as we advised numerous times for them to leave the "fragile" decorations alone. From sword fighting to rolling around on top of them, every time we would be out of sights range, someone would have to be rough-housing with one of all three of these decorations. Not sure why this was, it just seemed as though these had some kind of hypnotic pull that kept my children coming for them at every turn.  Finally they were hidden away until the day of the party, which ended up being one of the windiest outdoor parties ever, with 60 mph gusts at times, even tarps surrounding pavilion of park could not keep the horrendous winds from blowing everything, including decorations. For these guys, hanging from the top of the pavilion in a triangular formation, they may have gotten some of the worst drafts being higher than some of the tarps extended.  Even so, with so much abuse already dealt to the hapless shark blow-ups, at clean up time the sharks were taken down and remained full of air. Some days later, I found the blue shark inflatable in my Daughter's toy box, tail tied in a knot, yet most of it, everything above the tail still had air in it, as did the other inflatables.  Once kids found inflatables' third hiding spot, with the heat of summer bearing down, the pool became their common hang-out spot complete with the inflatable sharkswhere they continued to use throughout July and into August. I guess I could've continued to remove the items and find yet another hiding spot, but by then, I figured at least the inflatables are being put to good use other than the one-time birthday decoration they were intended to be. It is now almost September, with Summer winding down and school around the corner, the sharks are now lying quietly in the pool-deck box, they still contain most of their air that was originally blown into them more than 2 months earlier, with no additional air being applied, and through all the play and well...abuse to put it mildly, they seem to be still going strong. Completely worth the minimal price paid, with more uses than decorations, who knew? Definitely worth the money! While I wouldn't buy them specifically for use as an inflatable toy, just know they may be utilized in that fashion once their primary function has been performed! Recycling is great in any form!!

product_title: Cell Block Psycho Kids Costume
review_headline: Painfully Cruel to Those Living with Mental Illness
review_body: I am writing to share a serious matter of importance as it relates to one of your children’s costumes.  I refer to your Cell Block Psycho children’s costume with the description that reads, "Kids will look psychotic with our scary Cell Block Psycho Child Costume. With a look resembling Hannibal Lector, no other convict will dare mess with this one. Our kids' Cell Block Psycho Costume includes an orange prisoner jumpsuit featuring torn sleeves, one attached tattoo sleeve, zipper front and 'Ward 10-31 print, broken wrist shackle and a brown half face constraint mask. The molded plastic half mask features bars over the mouthpiece cutout for the scary look of Hannibal Lector the cannibal. No one on their cell block will dare to mess with this serial kill mental patient in our scary Cell Block Psycho Costume for kids." My younger daughter, once an honor student, athlete and musician before her illness presented during the onset of adolescence, has lived with schizoaffective disorder for the past six years, and was hospitalized as a child.  We’ve taken her to UCLA and Stanford, as well as our local hospitals, hoping to make sense of her devastating illness.  If you have ever spent anytime visiting a loved one in a children’s/adolescent’s mental health treatment facility, I assure you, you would understand that this costume is painfully cruel. Childhood suffering is not an appropriate inspiration for a Halloween costume.  Vampires are not real.  Mummies come-to-life, monsters and zombies are not real.  Cartoon characters, fairy princesses and action heroes are not real.  Those types of costumes are appropriate to sell for children for Halloween.  But childhood and adolescent mental illness is very real.  I doubt you would sell a Stage Four Cancer costume.  Why would you sell a costume that makes fun of a severe brain disorder? Stigma only encourages hopelessness and despair.  Please reconsider stigmatizing our daughter’s very real illness by removing your Cell Block Psycho Costume and other mental illness inspired costumes from your inventory.

product_title: LeapFrog Scout's Build and Discover Tool Set Toy
review_body:
The LeapFrog Scout's Build and Discover Tool Set is a dog house that can be taken apart and rebuilt.
I think this is a really novel idea to teach higher level concepts of construction, counting and color matching tools to the job. You get five tools: a hammer, ruler, saw, screwdriver and wrench.

This is not an erector set where you literally have to find pieces and fit them together using the appropriate tools to fasten them.
The walls just fold down (and handle separates) and the youngster is encouraged to use puppy pal Scout to guide them through counting and measuring.
Nothing is literally being hammered or screwed into place. Yet in imaginative play, there is a feeling of accomplishment when the thing comes back together.

One thing I am sort of surprised with (since this is a LeapFrog product) is a general lack of interactivity.
We have other LeapFrog products that use various mechanisms to respond to being pressed in certain spots or under certain conditions. I don't see those features with this item. This one is obviously intended for a younger age range. I think this would be good for a 2,3 or 4 year old.

Overall - this was well-received by my grandson. He seemed kind of in awe with it and (since he is on the younger side of that range), was excited when guided through "building" the dog house. I find the tools everywhere as he must be reasoning that if he can build a doghouse he can build other things.

product_title: VTech Go! Go! Smart Wheels Ultimate RC Speedway
review_body:
This set was a hit with the little ones. The pieces fit together well and the whole set appears durable. The nieces and nephews (ages 2-6) have played with it pretty regularly for the last two weeks and the set seems to be holding up well. The remote is well enough designed for use by an eighteen month old... it goes forwards - and backwards (not much to mess up)!!! As the adult... be prepared to tolerate a little noise with this as well..the car is a bit loud. Still, I definitely recommend it for design, durability, and repeated use and interest!!

Caveats: The instruction sheet is a bit small and hard to follow, but the picture on the box should be enough!! Consider putting it together the first time WITHOUT the little ones around to help!! It took around 30 minutes just to get all of the three sheets of stickers in the proper places... If you do get this, consider getting a good size storage box. This has a pretty large footprint and is the kind of setup that you will probably leave up for a few days at a time rather than putting up every night.

All the best,

Jay

product_title: Disney Frozen Elsa's Ice Palace Playset
review_headline: and of course little items like goblets, chests
review_body:
This might be the largest and most accurate Elsa Ice Palace I have seen.

The main component of this castle is spinning platform on the bottom that you attach the doll to. As you spin her around the second level of the castle also raises up (or down if you're cranking the other way). There are steps up the side that are spring loaded (when you touch the first step it flips the stairs over into a slide), an elsa portrait that turns around into a mirror, an Olaf portrait that is hidden behind a shade. A drop down chandelier. Plus it comes with a few little accessories, day bed, makeup station/stool, and of course little items like goblets, chests, etc.

Putting it together is fairly straightforward, some of the pieces are small and the directions aren't super clear, but it went together quite easily. The best part is that you don't have to put any stickers on.

So the final verdict. It looks like Elsa's Ice Castle, it's quite huge and has a lot of room for playing with 12" (i.e. Barbie size) dolls. The downside that we see is some of the plastic pieces don't feel all that sturdy, and the weight of the chandelier portion really seems to tilt the castle a bit, kind of making it look like a large piece of cheap plastic toy. Our daughter still loves it of course, but I feel it's really not justified of it's price tag.

product_title: Too Many Cinderellas Card Game
review_headline: Who will your Cinderella be... Perhaps a cat?
review_body:
Too Many Cinderellas by Grail Games. This tabletop game is for 2-4 players that are ages 10 + (My 8 yr plays), and is about 10 mins long. You play as town people who are spreading rumors for the Prince to hear. He will pick his Cinderella based off of the rumors that you spread. Anyone can actually become Cinderella. A male, senior, or even a cat. Yes, an actual meow cat! Which is my daughters favorite card from this game.

I was actually quite surprised how great the quality of this game is. The box is made out of a thick cardboard with beautiful bright prints. Once you open it up. All the components fit nicely and won’t be rattling around in your box. The art work on the lien cards are just beautiful! They use light pastel colors that most princess loving girls enjoy. The “diamonds” were both of the girls favorite components. They wanted them all. What girl can turn down the silliness and cuteness of the game!

Too Many Cinderellas is similar in scope to the Love Letter games. It is a quick, small deck based game where you earn the most tokens (diamonds) over a few rounds to win. Each card you lay down has an action, in this case a rumor. It’s easy enough to talk and enjoy your company while playing. However, it’s interesting enough to keep you pulling it out to play again. We truly enjoyed this game. I hope you check it out for yourself, or for a little girl in your life. My daughter & I like taking this out to our "coffee" dates.

Ages: 10 & up (though my 8 yr old plays)
Players: 2-4
Playing Time: 10 minutes
Materials: This game is very well made.
Recommend it to others: Yes, Quick fun games that is great for princess fans.

product_title: Pathfinder Adventure Card Game: Wrath of the Righteous Base Set
review_headline: A fun but incredibly demanding card game
review_body:
As other reviewers have noted, this is a game that's not particularly friendly to newcomers. Even simply setting up a game takes a ton of time; between creating up to six different "location" decks and up to four player decks, you'll be spending a LOT of time sorting through cards. Some decks even require you to pick out specific cards from the dozen or so different card categories, so overall the process can get pretty tedious.

Once we finally got a game going, though, it was pretty fun. The basic objective is to search a variety of locations for the villain, fight him a few times, close locations that he might escape to, and eventually kill him. Combat can get really intense -- your success is governed by a mixture of a character's strength, die rolls, and spending valuable cards to increase your chances of success. That said, I felt like luck played a little too strong a role in the success or failure of an encounter; the strength of a die roll is where you'll get the vast majority of your combat power, and this might turn off some players.

Pathfinder has some really cool ideas, and I particularly like how it handles the concept of "health" and "equipment." You can carry multiple weapon and armor cards with you in your hand, though you can only bring a limited number of those into an actual battle. As for your character's health, your draw deck essentially doubles as this. Taking damage forces you to discard cards from your hand, and if you run out of cards to draw... you're dead.

I'd like to reiterate that this is NOT a game that's easy to just jump right into. The rules are incredibly complex, and a lot of attention must be devoted to making sure that everything that's supposed to happen actually happens. (Since there are so many cards on the table at once, it's very easy to forget to trigger a particular event, and correcting mistakes like this is not always easy.)

My only other real problem with Pathfinder is that I found the artwork to be kind of bland. Monsters, characters, weapons, etc. are drawn on a plain white background, and the world of Pathfinder itself didn't jump out at me as anything special.

I should also mention that there's a persistent aspect of the game that involves permanently leveling up character cards, progressing through different scenarios, and even permanently removing cards from the game. I haven't checked this mode out yet myself, but there certainly seems to be a ton of content here. If you're willing to invest the time, you'll be getting some great bang for your buck.

product_title: LEGO Star Wars 75055 Imperial Star Destroyer Building Toy  (Discontinued by manufacturer)
review_headline: Great LEGO toy, and here is how to handle the "squeaky jammed hinge" issue.
review_body: Top-notch Lego set for STAR WARS Fans.  Build difficulty and intricacies: Medium, but needs teenager at least. - Though a young child can put most of it together, a teenager at least is needed to optimise the build. See below. - My 5.5 year old took about 7.5 hours to complete this. This is the same time as the UCS B-Wing, even though the UCS is arguably more complicated. This is because of the issue with the pegs that make up the lateral fold-out joints of the hull. - These pegs cannot be pushed all the way into the socket. If you inspect them carefully, there is a small bulge just below the head of the peg. If you push the peg all the way into the socket, it jams the hinge and any attempt to fold out the hull not only causes an annoying squeaking noise, the resistance exerts stress on the Lego plates that often leads to parts of the hull falling off whenever you fold it out. After discovering this, I had to disassemble the adjacent sections of the hull plates and ask my son to re-do it again (which is why it took him as long as it did). 95% into the socket is enough.  Play value: High, considering the size of the set. - a Command Centre section that lifts off to reveal the interior, and the upper hull plates folding outward and down to reveal the rest. - two spring-loaded missiles that fire forward, with storage for two more at the rear of the bridge. - swivelling turbolaser cannons on both sides - Many minifigures  Display value-for-money: High. - It isn't the same as the UCS Star Destroyer, but it looks impressive and detailed.  Trivia (for Star Wars vehicle buffs): - The proportions of the Bridge and the swivelling turbolaser cannons fit the blueprints of a Victory-Class Star Destroyer rather than an Imperial Star Destroyer. (See the Star Wars Vehicles and Vessels diagrams.) This is a minor point really, and does not detract from the beauty of this set.

product_title: LeapFrog Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles Imagicard Learning Game and Bonus Booster Pack
review_headline: I've been impressed with all the LeapFrog products we've used
review_body:
The product itself comes in a really nice little metal box, with a stack of sturdy cards (and instructions) inside. One card has a little scratch-off code that you use to download the game to your LeapPad Platinum Tablet. The cards are fairly sturdy, but might not hold up to the normal use from a typical 5 year old. An 8 year old should be able to care for them well. What is nice, though, is that with the "Digital Card Picker" you don't actually have to HAVE the card to choose to play with it, so losing (or mangling) a card doesn't render the game useless.

LeapFrog is a company we've been using for about fifteen years, and I'm always impressed with how they keep adapting to current technology, and also keeping up with characters that are currently popular. Mixing Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles with math is definitely a good way to get kids to pay some attention.

You can use the cards to play some games without the pad too. My kids have fun with using the cards to build equations. I like that there are signs for division and multiplication, and there are also fractions.

product_title: LEGO Star Wars 75049 Snowspeeder Building Toy (Discontinued by manufacturer)
review_headline: Good model of my favorite SW vehicle.
review_body:
Most people love the Millennium Falcon. The X-Wing is a perennial favorite. And then there are the contrary types who prefer the Star Destroyer. But for me, my favorite Star Wars vehicle has always been the Snowspeeder. It just has that aggressive wedge-shape, with the two ginormous guns mounted and the nifty maneuvering flaps that suggest serious maneuverability. The looks just scream "home brew hot rod," even more than the X-wing, showing the philosophical differences between the Rebels (individual modifications) and the Empire (ruthless conformity and standardization). Yes, I have to say...the Snowspeeder is first in my heart, and LEGO has done a decent job here.

That said, this particular set is not without problems. The instructions need just a touch more proofreading, as I noticed at least one spot where a sticker placement was just not listed. In addition, I always found it easier to affix the sticker to the brick and then add it to the model...these instructions generally tell you to place the brick first and *then* add the sticker. For some of the elements, like inside the cockpit, this doesn't work very well. Also, the instructions aren't clear on how to use the harpoon gun - we here had to reason it out that the reason the extra piece was on the grapple was to fit in the gun, after which you press the lever and it shoots out of there.

Second issue I had is the harpoon - yes, the line is fine on its own but in conjunction with other sets, yep, like a previous reviewer said you'll find it too short. You can certainly hack this by adding your own longer string, but then you run into design issues in that the spool isn't big enough to accommodate much more than the string that is provided. Using thinner string is an option, but then you sacrifice durability.

The added value here are the three minifigures (my oldest remarked on the detail of the snowtrooper, and I have to say he's really cool), but at this point I have to give another nit and complain about the trend of two-faced LEGO heads. Why? In this case, the helmets of Luke and Dak do not completely cover the back of their heads, so you see their chins peeking through on the backs of their heads. It was a cute idea when I first saw it with the femme fatale figure in an Indiana Jones set, but now I think it's just getting overdone.

Another value add are the missile launchers - they work and are easy, if not entirely accurate to the ESB film. Still, kind of neat to launch them across the room, and yes they do have pretty good range for their sizes.

So overall, this is a very good set. Building does require more attention than usual because of the instructions, but the end result is a pretty sturdy ship with great play value.oint I have to give another nit and complain about the trend of two-faced LEGO heads. Why? In this case, the helmets of Luke and Dak do not completely cover the back of their heads, so you see their chins peeking through on the backs of their heads. It was a cute idea when I first saw it with the femme fatale figure in an Indiana Jones set, but now I think it's just getting overdone.

Another value add are the missile launchers - they work and are easy, if not entirely accurate to the ESB film. Still, kind of neat to launch them across the room, and yes they do have pretty good range for their sizes.

So overall, this is a very good set. Building does require more attention than usual because of the instructions, but the end result is a pretty sturdy ship with great play value.

product_title: Pokemon Eevee Evolution Umbreon Anime Animals Plush Plushies Stuffed Doll Toy 8"
review_body:
I recently got this Umbreon in the mail last month. He came pretty quick despite that he came all the way from China. China may be famous for it's bootlegs, but I do love this guy quite a lot! Heck, he even goes good with my Espeon plush, or any Eevee plush collection or a collection of other Eevee merchandise. Like I said earlier, Umbreon did come fast and he came from a pretty reliable seller as well!

This Umbreon plush is very soft, but the stuffing is somewhat stiff though. He is well constructed, but there are some flaws with him, All the rings on his body, except for one, which was flawed a little bit, were perfectly made. His red eyes are beautiful yet fierce looking for a Dark type Pokemon, similar to a cat's eyes. He sadly does not stand up well and does tumble often due to his paws not being pointed down and rather being in a straight line.

Note: There are more bootlegs of this Umbreon plush than authentic ones. The ones that are sold on Amazon and eBay are mainly being sold by Chinese vendors. If you want an authentic one from Japan or the Pokemon Center USA website and not a bootleg from China or Hong Kong, you could be out of luck. The bootlegs are much cheaper, and if you order one, it could be poorly made.

Despite being a counterfeit Umbreon plush, this was worth the money. Any Eevee or Umbreon fan will be pleased with this.

review_headline: I would recommend this product for both homeschool parents and teachers
review_body: I would recommend this product for both homeschool parents and teachers.  The educational value of the Chunky Magnet Set is high just as a manipulative, but gets much higher when you add the activity cards!  As a magnet it functions perfectly.  Sometimes magnets encased in plastic or surrounded by plastic are weaker or less reliable, the Chunky Magnet does everything you would expect a magnet to do and more!  It has a nice feel to it and all the parts are designed well for big or little hands.  Cheaper magnet sets are out there, but then you have small hard to organize parts that are not worth it.  I recommend this magnet set over the many others I have tried.  My sixth grade students use it during free time just to explore and play, which is great, but I am already planning to incorporate it into my math and STEM classes.

product_title: Disney Lilo and Stitch Angel Plush Toy 9"
review_headline: Sweet Little Angel Plushie -- Such a Softie! :)
review_body:
I always loved "Lilo and Stitch", and have fond memories of watching the cartoon on TV as a child.
Experiment 624, known as Angel, from the classic Disney television cartoon “Lilo and Stich: The Series”, is Stitch’s adorable and pretty feminine counterpart. This lovely plushie of her is quite difficult to come by, so when she showed up at the Disney Store in my local mall, I purchased her right away. I picked her up, held her, and just couldn’t leave without her – I am indeed happy that I bought her! She goes well with my Stitch plush and is very nice to hug and cuddle. She is a roughly medium-sized plush, about 10 inches tall, a bit smaller than the Disney Store Stitch plush (despite being just as large as Stitch as portrayed in the cartoon). However, the quality of this plush toy is just spectacular.

This is probably the best plushie of Angel you will ever find. She is accurate, authentic, and absolutely adorable. She is made with a velvety fabric that is sublimely soft to the touch. Her hot-pink colours are very vivid and emphasize her girlish charm, differentiating her from her boy counterpart, Stitch.

She is very pudgy and cuddly, with a rounded body shape. She is stuffed so that she is very squishy-soft and huggable, yet she retains her shape perfectly, as she is very well-constructed and durable.

The details are wonderful! This sweet little mischievous girl alien, Angel, has a koala-like look about her, just like Stitch. She has big black eyes with little lashes, a big round lavender purplish nose, and super-soft, long rounded rabbit-like ears. Her colouration and markings are spot-on. Most of her body is a vivid hot-pink colour, her underbelly, inner ears, and the rings around her eyes are a soft rose shade, her blunt claws and paw pads are magenta, and she has purplish patches on her antennae and ear tips. She has a white heart-shaped mark on her chest, and another large purple upside-down heart-shaped mark on her back.

I particularly love her long, gracefully flowing tendril-like antennae, as well as her cute lil’ bob-tail.
One of the paw pads on her feet has an official Disney Store logo on it, so you can tell it is the authentic product.

This is a truly adorable and wonderful plushie, and I highly recommend it to fans of Lilo and Stitch. Children and collectors alike will love this Angel plushie.

(I just really wish the Disney Store would release a big chubby, fluffy plush toy of Experiment 625 (a.k.a. “Reuben”), Captain Gantu’s witty sandwich-making sidekick, who appeared in nearly ALL of the “Lilo and Stitch: The Series” episodes (whereas Angel only appeared in two of them), and is super-cute! He is so funny and adorable, and so lovable, plump, and cuddly-looking -- I don’t understand why there wouldn’t be a plushie of Reuben! I would love to have one. . .)mark on her back.

I particularly love her long, gracefully flowing tendril-like antennae, as well as her cute lil’ bob-tail.
One of the paw pads on her feet has an official Disney Store logo on it, so you can tell it is the authentic product.

This is a truly adorable and wonderful plushie, and I highly recommend it to fans of Lilo and Stitch. Children and collectors alike will love this Angel plushie.

(I just really wish the Disney Store would release a big chubby, fluffy plush toy of Experiment 625 (a.k.a. “Reuben”), Captain Gantu’s witty sandwich-making sidekick, who appeared in nearly ALL of the “Lilo and Stitch: The Series” episodes (whereas Angel only appeared in two of them), and is super-cute! He is so funny and adorable, and so lovable, plump, and cuddly-looking -- I don’t understand why there wouldn’t be a plushie of Reuben! I would love to have one. . .)

product_title: Fisher Price Disney Minnie - Fabulous Minnie Mall
review_headline: Not Up to Fisher Price Standards ...
review_body: I was a little astonished to see the Fisher Price name on this toy ... one that sports a Fisher Price price tag. Were it not for the actual label, this product feels a little like something one might pick-up at a Big Lots, an Ollies or an Odd Lot (you know, those Unclaimed Freight type stores with the odd-ball, off-brand toys). It's flimsy, lacking attention to detail, and features lots of monochromatic plastic chunks that seem merely to take-up space rather than to be played with.  Also, for all of you expecting this "mall" to fold in half with a little pop-up handle for travel ... no such thing.  The one aspect they "got right" was the inclusion of more than one figure. Parents have been complaining for years about these Disney themed sets that then require mom and dad to pick up extra figures (rightly so). Here, Minnie and Daisy are included. Nice touch.  Now, do know that it is from China. I know many, many parents who will not permit their children to have such toys due to the substandard manufacturing processes (that does seem to be an issue here), human rights violations, and frequent recalls.  This was ignored and discarded pretty quickly by the little ones. It seems, "what am I supposed to do with it?" was the reigning answer. And, I can hardly argue. I don't see many activities here ... and I don't see aspects that spark imagination. For us, on nearly every level, this was not a success.

product_title: Rainbow Star Wand for Fairy or Princess Costume by RIN
review_body: I had fifteen dollars lying around and my best friend's address, so I ordered this for him. I had it gift-wrapped, added a letter, and sent it to his house. It came to his door one day BEFORE the estimated delivery date (and it shipped to the east coast from California). The box was much larger than the product (great for storage, thanks Amazon). The gift wrapping was high quality and matched the classic Amazon colors (I'm saving it for this Christmas).  For a single-piece plastic item, my friend was very impressed with the packing, it was surrounded in wrapping paper and air cushions (re-gifted as toys for my pets). He said the wand itself came exactly as pictured and the plastic felt very durable, with the star and handle are one molded piece and very hard to break apart. The rainbow gradient would match any pink or purple fairy, princess, witch, or stripper costume. At first I did not believe him.  My friend gave this to his younger sister (she is 18 months old) when she was crying. Not only did she stop crying, she was intrigued by the amazing build quality of this magic wand and played with it for the next 30 minutes. An hour later, my friend found it in his goldfish bowl, with Mr. Goldy (his pet goldfish) swimming through and around it. Holding it from the top end, my friend was able to use it as a replacement drum stick when one of his broke, until he could get a new wooden one.  I truly believe it is a five-star product. At such a cheap price, it comes out on top - compared to other magic or costume wands anywhere. I visited his house and he showed me this wand I bought for him. I was amazed at not only the amazing quality of this product, but also at the fact my friend was telling the truth.  This product is now in an antique display case above the headboard of his bed, being saved for the generations that will follow him, to spare them from the fate of horrible, ever-expanding Chinese build quality.  Here are 13 reasons you should consider buying this item: 1. Great for any fairy/princess costume. 2. Toys for your pet dog or cat. 3. Shipping Box large enough for future storage or moving. 4. Durable plastic, capable of receiving abuse. 5. Exactly as pictured, excluding white backdrop. 6. Brilliantly colored rainbow gradient. 7. Great centerpiece for a room. 8. Decent temporary drum stick. 9. Entertainment for a small child. 10. Good aquarium prop for a small goldfish. 11. Reestablishes trust with close friends. 12. Spares you from cheap, Chinese toys. 13. Madly hilarious entertainment for a teenager (16).  CONS: 1. There was no instruction manual. 2. It is not a six-point star.  For the $15 I spent on this product, the return on investment is astounding.

product_title: Magic The Gathering: Arena of the Planeswalkers Game
review_headline: Great game, 23 years in the making
review_body:
This is the game that Wizards of the Coast always wanted to make.

When I received the first, beta-version of Magic the Gathering from Rich back in 1992, I thought to myself this is a card game version of WizWar, where magicians challenge each other by casting spells and summoning creatures to fight one another.

After 23 years, this is the board game for Magic the Gathering.

I like it. I like it a lot.

As with all WotC products, the quality of the components is very high.

Each player take the role of a Planeswalker (wizard) that summons creatures and spells to attack opponents.

Once your points are gone, you are out of the game.

Last wizard standing is the winner.

The rules are simple, but they game is infused with the themes and flavor of the collectible card game.

There is lots and lots of room for expansions, but the base rules are less than ten pages long and those pages are liberally filled with colorful diagrams and photos.

Great game! I highly recommend it!
