product_title: Miles From Tomorrowland Stellosphere
review_headline: Fun addition/companion to watching the Disney Junior series
review_body:
I was surprised when this arrived because it is much bigger that I was expecting.
The Miles From Tomorrowland Stellosphere falls into the category of imaginative play for space lovers who watch the Disney Junior series.
Not familiar with the series? Miles from Tomorrowland is an animated space adventure series. It centers on the Callisto family who live on a spaceship called the Stellosphere and work for the Tomorrowland Transit Authority (TTA).

From the description, "The Stellosphere comes apart into 3 separate ships to make space explorations easier. Open up the large Stellosphere playset to reveal the Callisto's command center where Miles and the Callisto Family (figures sold separately) can receive missions from the TTA. For short, quick missions, take the mini StarJetter that is stored in the Stellosphere. For longer missions that require a greater distance to travel take the Zip Ship that can be removed from the top of the Stellosphere. To boost any ship with lights and sounds remove the XVR system from the bottom of the Stellosphere and attach to the other ships."

First, the Stellosphere requires 3 AAA batteries which are included.
There is one poseable Miles figure included. Miles is an enthusiastic and curious boy with a somewhat reckless inventive streak whom the series is named after.

The Stellosphere has a lot of features. It has lights and sounds plus phrases from "Miles from Tomorrowland".
I think this is a really fun and imaginative concept - the ability to detach the ships is a great feature, especially when multiple kids are playing.

I am very happy with all aspects of this item.
There is a play set of other figures but they are stuck to little platforms and not as poseable as Miles from this set. Other action figures from this series do fit / match. There are also companion toys that go with this Stratosphere for the real Miles fan.

product_title: The Original Slinky Brand Metal Slinky 3 Pack
review_body:
Pros: It's a Slinky. The three-pack does contain three separately
boxed Slinkys. It will go down stairs IF - the stair tread is not too
wide and if there is no loose pile carpet. Generally, this Slinky can't
make the leap far enough out to continue and it tends to catch on
the carpet fibers. Considering the $1.00 price back in the '40s when
Slinky was introduced, the $10. price for three is not out-of-line.

Cons: This new "original" Slinky is not like the original "original".
Although the box says it is original, the 1945 version had a total
of 98 coils, this one has only 72 coils. That rather severely limits
the "action".

The SIZE of the present "original" is 2 3/4" diameter x 2 1/16"
tall. Held by one end and suspended, it stretches to 43 inches.
It's not the same as the inventor designed. SHAME.

product_title: Knit’s Cool - Knitting Studio
review_headline: New to knitting, got a bit complicated.
review_body:
Overall, I think this product does what is advertised. I received this product from BzzAgent. My 8 year old had it opened and assembled almost immediately. I decided I would give it a try before I let her have it since the odds were good that she would need a little help. I do not sew or knit or really have a desire to do either so this is not a natural task for me and my first attempt at using this product showed it. The instructions were difficult to follow even with the colorful pictures (again, I am completely incompetent at anything sewing or knitting or related). I put it away after frustration set in and tried it again a couple days later. The 2nd attempt went a little better. I obviously did not catch that each project called for a certain pole size but finally realized it several stitches into the project. So on came round 3. Round 3 had much better results although it was definitely a "first attempt" looking project.

As for the projects. The project that we have completed so far is the headband. It turned out okay but it was way too big using the instructions provided. I would recommend about 3/4 of the way through to start gauging the size so that you will actually be able to use it.

In regards to the product design, I liked it and so did the 8 year old. All of the posts store nicely into the base and everything seems to have it's place. The one thing that we didn't understand though is why the smallest of the posts were provided. None of the projects call for that size post and there is really no explanation as to why you would need that size. I can only assume that maybe there is extra yarn with extra patterns or something that you can buy that would use them. Otherwise, they seem useless.

This is a product that I would have seen and immediately knew that my 8 year old would love. She loves this kind of thing and she was not disappointed.

product_title: North American Bear Dolly Pockets Goldilocks and The 3 Bears Plush
review_body: Oh my, we have a little girl in this house who is madly in love with this doll. It is amazing. This is a girl who really wants to like dolls, but never finds one that she really wants to "own." But not this doll. She carries this girl around all over the place, including in the car, to bed, on a hike, yep, pretty much everywhere. She just loves the apron with the three little bears in it. The doll itself is the perfect size for carrying around and is squeezable and soft.  The little bear finger puppets are so cute, with simple details (like a denim bottom half for the papa bear and a pink bow and pink patterned bottom for the momma bear) that makes them interesting and fun to look at. The little puppets are simply sewn into her pockets, but it is just a few loops of thread, so they can be easily snipped if you want them out all the way. You can pop them out of the pocket and keep them sewn in, which is what I am planning on doing, since so much of the charm is in having those bears in her pockets. And charming is overall the perfect word for this adorable doll!

product_title: Mini Keychain 3*3*3 Rubik Cube Puzzle Magic Game Toy
review_body:
I wasn't expecting anything very durable, but this was even flimsier that I thought it would be. I didn't want to actually play with it. I wanted to hang it from a keychain. I wanted to use a ball chain rather than the key chain that came with it. Unfortunately the little screw eye was too tiny for the chain to fit through. I took it out and replaced it with a larger one and anchored it in place with epoxy. About that time the whole cube fell apart. The pieces would not go back into place and stay, so I just super glued the whole thing together. It still looks like a Rubik's Cube, but now it's a super solid single cube that is not going to fall apart again. In the photo you can see where I tried to mount the screw eye in the middle. That did not work. That is what pushed the pieces apart. (OK, that was my fault, not the manufacturer's.)

Bottom line: If you just want something to hang from your keychain this will work. Don't plan on actually playing with it much.

product_title: Travel Scrabble (New Version)
review_headline: Nice Travel Board but mediocre racks!
review_body:
As compact and travel-like as advertised.
Major Shortfall is the rack. The racks are so small and not long enough that the tiles cannot be properly positioned on them without falling off occasionally.
They could have cut down on the fancy part of the rack covering and simply made it the usual rack we all know, but wider and more accommodating of the tiles.

Other than that, I can't fault the board at all. Nice touch on the folding feature. Tiles fit perfectly in the board squares, and won't move if shaken. The board can also be covered with the tiles remaining exactly where they are. This is nice.

There's a small compartment within as well, I guess to store stuff. Don't see much going in there for me though except for a pen and paper.

So yeah, it's a miniature travel board as advertised. The main demerit is the inconvenience in using the racks. An alternative though might be to use bigger racks instead of the one included.

Cheers!

review_headline: and it goes on smooth & looks fine.
review_body: This comes in the mail in a small box with the fabric canvas folded, paints, brushes, number guide, and a tiny 3 1/4" x  4 1/4" picure of completed product. The canvas appears to be possibly a type of vinyl laminated to an even weave fabric. It comes folded up & the folds are creased into the fabric. It has to be stretched to eliminate the folds, which involves purchasing something to stretch it with. I used a frame  meant for working cross stitch or needlepoint, which meant rolling it onto the bars & having to roll it several times to put the creases in the center & roll & lock tight, then turn it sideways & repeat process. All but the center crease came out this way & that is more of a roll in the fabric now than a crease. So I am going to try putting it back on the frame again for a longer period of time. I left it on for each crease for 1 day. This is timely & I'm sure there is something out there that is meant for stretching fabric. Possibly a quilting product? I did paint a small area to see how the paint went onto this type of canvas, and it goes on smooth & looks fine.

product_title: Magnetic Stick N Stack Magnetic Tiles Starter set With 4 Windows, 60 Piece, Red, Orange, Blue, Green & Yellow
review_headline: Wonderful toy. Fun for all ages!
review_body: These are well worth the money spent.  Of all the gifts our daughter received for her 3rd birthday, this set has been played with the most. Every child who visits the house is instantly drawn to these colourful tiles. They are also appealing to adults, and I often find myself on the floor joining in the fun. They are stacked into towers, flown as airplanes, and crafted into homes for Littlest Pet Shops (The pets with magnets on their feet can stick to the tiles!)  Interestingly, the box they came in had the wrong quantities listed on it. We actually got 32 (not 26) small squares, 2 large squares, 4 windows, 10 (not 12) small triangles, 8 (not 10) long triangles, and 4 (not 6) wide triangles. This, to me, is a bonus, as the small squares are the most popular pieces for building up.  Though they are not too easy on the wallet, considering the hours of play value they provide, they are absolutely worth the cost. We have ordered more for our children to expand the range of creations they can make. Highly recommended!

product_title: Cheerson CX-10 Mini 29mm Diameter 4CH 2.4GHz 6 Axis Gyro RC Quadcopter UFO RTF Green
review_body: The post is labeled Cheerson CX-10. If you click on "Color Options", you'll notice that instead of seeing Cheerson you'll see Pheonixtec for all other options except the first. These are NOT the same product! They are extremely similar, but there are minor differences. I mistakenly purchased a Pheonixtec quad by accident. After flying it for a total of approximately  ten flights I already began experiencing problems: They stabilization easily became off, causing it to suddenly pitch to one side or another, as well as drop and ascend without being commanded. Not a lot, around six inches. After medium impact crashes one blade of the quad would spin at full speed without being commanded. I would turn off the transmitter and it would not stop. The only way to stop it was too turn off the quad and then back on again. This happened multiple times. Avoid purchasing knock off versions of the original Cheerson. Aside from these problems caused by Pheonixtec, the product is excellent. I strongly recommend purchasing one, they're less than $20! Why not!? Just be sure to purchase a genuine Cheerson!

product_title: Pokemon Center Espeon 8" Plush Doll by Pokemon Center
review_body:
I have the authentic version of this plush, since I bought it on the Pokemon Center USA website. I usually don't mind bootlegs, but the bootleg version of the Pokemon Center Espeon Poke Plush has a lopsided head unlike the one that I have. Espeon is my favorite Eeveeloution alongside Sylveon, Leafeon and Umbreon, and I thought that having a average size Espeon plush that's larger than the unofficial Espeon Poke Doll would be a wonderful gift for me, She looks just like a nekotama cat from Japanese mythology and folklore, and even more cute!

This Espeon plush is adorable and beautiful simultaneously. The wonderful purple/lilac minky fabric used to make her is luxuriously soft like every Pokemon Center licensed Pokemon plush! She's structured very well, even better than every other Espeon plush ever made.(The Kuttari Cuties Espeon plush, both awake and asleep forms, are ridiculously adorable too!) The stitching and shaping is satisfactory, and deserves an A+!

Also, if you want an authentic version of this plush instead of a bootleg one, you could possibly be out of luck. They are very rare to find and if you are lucky enough to find one, they are ridiculously expensive. Sadly, bootleg Pokemon plushies are a lot cheaper than the authentic ones.

If you ever get this plush, you should get her lunar counterpart, Umbreon, to go along with her. Even a Sylveon would go good with this plush too. This is definitely my No.1 favorite Eeveeloution in sweet and huggable plush form! Any Eeveeloution fan will be happy!

product_title: Silverlit Toys Nano Falcon
review_headline: ... expecting slightly less power but its quite strong not super fast but its very accurate and very very easy ...
review_body:
i was expecting slightly less power but its quite strong not super fast but its very accurate and very very easy to learn
its a lot of fun to fly around fans ceiling fans box fans and the oscillating fans made my own trials course with lots of controlled wind
the range seems great and unlike most of the infrared rc helicopers i've had this tiny one seems to keep its signal the best
charges quick
the light it has is very dim i dont know if that just mine or the fact that the led is just so small
you cant use it to navigate unless its totally pitch black it does help to locate it when its fallen into a dark area
the rotors seem durable its fallen from quite a distance and has had no signs of damage

i love this controller out of all the cheaper helicopers ive had and used this simple one takes the cake well done
the charging plug flops there is no notch to hold it in place when in the fully upright position
the battery last a good while i start out hovering at maybe 30% throttle tops and by 5-7 minutes im pushing it at 70-80% throttle just to keep it in the air they did a good job syncing battery level and throttle power

the metal charging plug it self is very small and seems like it can break very easily and be a good reason to have a second charger around
this is the only thing i can see breaking easily with little kids
the tail is solid but the motor is not super strong but seems to do the job

age rating 10+
fun rating for all ages 9/10
(could be faster may need to upgrade motors)

product_title: Syma S107/S107G  R/C Helicopter with Gyro
review_headline: Nice indoor flyer for the price point.
review_body:
This helicopter is truly wonderful for its price point. Flying it is easy, if not particularly helicopter like, you only have throttle (left hand) , forward/reverse and rudder (right hand). There's no sideways flight as in a real helicopter or quadcopter. The downside, if there is one, is it isn't much of an outdoor flier - it is strongly affected by wind and sunlight will disrupt the infrared control signal, you if you want to go outside, you will want calm overcast (or evening hours) days.

It seems to hold up OK in crashes, but I always kill the throttle when I think a crash is about to happen. it does come with extra blades, I haven't had to use them yet.

product_title: Ubongo - Sprint to Solve the Puzzle
review_body:
Ubongo is a fun addition to our family's game cabinet. It's a quick (about 20 minutes) and competitive game that my husband and I enjoy. The puzzles themselves are fun and generally take well under a minute, at least at the easier level. The timer and gems add complexity - but I think whether that's a good thing depends on your taste. We opted to play without the timer; whoever solved first won that round. Drawing gems added an element of chance, which could easily mean the difference in the outcome for evenly matched competitors. Two levels (puzzles with 3 or 4 pieces) mean you can adjust difficulty - and provide a way for my son to play against me more evenly.

I hold back from five stars because it isn't our favorite, but Ubongo is a game we'll play again and enjoy.

product_title: Team Associated SC10 RS Toyota Racing RTR Truck
review_headline: Everything you need nothing you dont
review_body: When I walked into my LHS which has a large off road track, I asked the guy behind the counter about what would be fun to run behind my house and competitive at the track. Being a newbie to the RC world I wasn't looking to spend alot of money. They had some less expensive short course trucks and naturally asked about them first. He told me if I was just looking to bash in the backyard the 200$ SC they sold would be a great truck, if I was looking to race then the Team Associated SC10RS would be a better choice. The guy said he been doing RC for 30 years. I asked if I bought this could I just drop it on the track and be competitive? He assured me I could.  My brother and I both bought this truck that day, his the Rock Star/Makita version mine this very Toyota. We raced with them stock a week later and even though we were complete noobs we still placed better than last against guys running hopped up losi's and 200$ transmitters. After some rigorous practice and new tires that better fit the track, i'm now running mid pack, slowly moving up every week, well my brother has taken 2 first place finishes in the 3 weeks we've raced.  I'm confident with time I'll be in the front of the pack and my truck is not what is holding me back. I catch everyone in the straight and can turn as tight as anything out there. I run 5300ma 40C lipo batteries. I recommend  at least 40 C battery as this car definitely shows an improvement in punch on the 40c over a 30c battery. Running less than a 30c battery will overstress the battery and definitely effect performance. The guy at the shop said more than a 40c battery won't show a performance boost or a very  negligible one. Sounds believable since he make more if he sold me a more expensive higher C battery.  As far as durability is concerned ive smashed this thing in every way conceivable. I did manage to rip the rear A arm off after about 4 weeks of running this thing to the hilt, and the lexon body cracked alot in the rear, but some gorilla tape fixed that right up. The rear A arms at my local track were only 7$ a set for the OEM ones. Besides that this thing has taken a beating and kept going. I've cycled multiple batteries through it in a row with out cool down time. The motor hasn't shown any loss of performance. I try to let it cool down now between runs since talking to experienced guys who told me running more than 10 minutes straight can damage a RC motor. The 5300ma lipos Batteries last easily 20+ minutes running close to wide open or wide open about 50% of the time on the track. The battery cut off has always left 6+ volts in my pack. I definitely wouldn't want to run them any lower since everything I've read online says 6V is OK but theirs alot of debate about anything lower and most agree its probably damaging your pack going lower.  The stock shell does suffer from "parachuting" when going off large jumps. Since the track I run on is set up for 1/8 buggy and truggy both electric and nitro the jumps are huge. You can hit most of them but it takes precise lining up and getting hard on the throttle as soon as possible. The truck is light enough that even though it's only rear wheel drive you do have a fair amount of control using the throttle and brake to adjust your angle mid air. Assuming that a strong wind doesn't come along and flip you over mid air or cause you too levitate. From what I've seen everyone either cuts holes in their body or most just use flo tech bodies to negate this issue. The stock body seems fine as long as its not windy, it is very predictable.  At the last race I went to it had rained hard for a few hours prior to race start. The track was muddy and not just regular mud but muddy clay. Durring qualifying my truck started having serious performance issues and at one point I watched it come through a left turn and as it rolled out I noticed the front left wheel dipped deep into the chassis at the apex of the corner. I thought I had blown a shock. After the race I picked up my car and it weighed nearly twice its normal weight. The entire inside of the shell and the rest of the truck from the rear end through the front suspension was caked in mud. The fan on the esc was even burried and not spinning. Well I cleaned it out with brushs the best I could but I still felt it was heavier than it should be. The fan came back to life though. On my 2nd race I noticed it still was not performing as well as it should and caked up again before it was over. So this time I just took it over to the hose and sprayed the whole truck out. Yeah I'm nuts, but you know what I let it dry till the next heat, popped a battery in it and it still worked like nothing happened. I took care not to spray directly into seals on the rear end, electronics, and survo. I'm not saying that you should hose your car right out like I did but I am saying that I did it and the car didn't skip a beat.  I can't say that I have alot of experience with short course trucks, the only other truck I have is a hpi Blitz that I got a great deal on used. I can tell you though from my experience this sc10RS has hop ups from the factory that are needed and none that it doesn't. It has aluminum shocks and a brushless motor which everyone agrees if you have a standard sc10 are 2 of the first things you should get. The survo in it is also fairly strong, and quick. It's not the most amazing thing you can buy but from what I've learned from other SC guys is it is the best survo that comes in any brand SC RTR. Also the transmitter, will not a 100$ or 200$ unit does feel smooth and has all the adjustment knobs you need. Mine came with the new style with the knobs on top so did my brothers. Also like I said earlier, my brother is running this thing full stock (minus tires) and that includes the transmitter and is laying a hurting on guys with mush more expensive equipment.  The only downside I've really seen with this truck is its transmission is loud compared to the blitz which hasfull metal gears and is filled with gear oil. The sc10s gears are mostly plastic and only runs a semi sealed designed. I don't believe this was done to save cost. The blitz weighs considerably more because of that full metal tranny which effects everything from acceleration to how will it jumps. I've had zero problems with the rear end in the sc10 and I beat on it as hard as I want. So plastic gears or not they hold up well. This is just a well built racer using metal only where it is absolutely crucial for durability. The only thing I upgraded were the wheel hexes in the back to aluminum ones. I chewed up my plastic ones running with the wheels lose and not realizing it. They also make wheel changing easier cause they lock onto the axle where as the plastic ones were only held in place by the wheel and tended to get stuck in the rim when the wheel was removed. It's a hop up for convenience more than anything and adds very little weight.  Oh and I should mention the esc will come loose on you if you run this thing hard as you should. The factory applied double sided tape is garbage. We bought scotch brand double sided outdoor rated tape and nothing has broken loose since. We also use it for our transponders. Get that and some gorrilla tape for reinforcing the shell if it cracks and you'll be all set.

product_title: Rio Grande Games Dominion
review_body:
A really great game, easy to play and teach (though it may seem daunting at first glance, it's really not). Also, inexpensive as games go, at least until you start going for all the expansion sets. The base game is a good solid start that'll keep you playing for quite a while, since there are 25 "kingdom" cards from which you use only 10 per game, so the number of variations is pretty good.

The thing to note about Dominion is, depending on what kingdom cards are in a given game, sets the stage for the strategy. Different strategies work in most cases, but part of the game is figuring out what will be the best strategy to choose given what kingdom cards are available to buy in that particular game. This also increases the replay value since you won't always be using the exact same strategy every game. And picking combinations of kingdom cards to play that work together to give you extra benefits is really fun to pull off.

Don't let the massive number of cards intimidate you-- the core part of the game of the Kingdom cards, you're only using 10 at a time, though there'll be a bunch of copies of each-- which makes it look a lot more complex than it really is. I taught it to a friend who within a couple of turns had it figured out and she ended up beating me using a kingdom card that I had been previously ignoring because it didn't seem that powerful (the Cellar)-- she saw the value of it where I didn't and ended up winning. A very fun game. If in doubt, try the online version, you can play the base game for free.

One thing to note: the base game will play 2-4. And as a 2-player it's excellent. You can go up to 8 players by combining the original set with Intrigue but I hear when going over 4 players it tends to bog down somewhat. I bought Intrigue because we do have 5 in our game group now and then, but haven't had a chance yet to figure out how good it is with 5, I'll probably try it but with a group of more than 5I'd probably either divide them up into two games (also possible with the Intrigue set, or even just by adding the base-card set).

All in all, a totally awesome game.

product_title: Diy home decor digital canvas oil painting by number kits Napoleon 16*20 inch.
review_headline: Regardless the Question, Art IS the Answer
review_body:
Just as I had imagined, I am able to put myself in the place of a fine classical painter, Jacques-Louis David in the Romanticism style.

I chose Napoleon Crossing the Alps (also known as Napoleon at the Saint-Bernard Pass or Bonaparte Crossing the Alps), because it is a complex composition depicting a pivotal moment of sublime metaphoric power and a grandiose version of a highly idealized seminal moment where Napoleon commands his place in the annals of history.

Being as the original was commissioned by the then King of Spain and several versions were made, I feel entitled to paint my own version proudly placing my own countenance in the place of Napoleon's. When my own travails seem more than I can bear, I will take heart and majestically push onward and cross that metaphoric pass on my bounding steed... (as my cat, Sparklefarts will now be nicknamed).

You might wonder, if she likes it so much why only 3 stars? And you would be correct in assuming something was indeed amiss.
The canvas received was not stapled onto wooden stretchers! The box contained a folded piece of canvas that I have to have staple to wooden stretchers that I'll have to purchase! Drat! Confounded dashed hopes!!! I have more problem solving with which to cope.

product_title: Air Hogs Smash Bots - Remote Control Battling Robots
review_body:
These Air Hogs Smash Bots were put the test by my 9 year old daughter (and then her 13 year old brother had to jump in to challenge her). The concept sounds cool, the reality ok but not quite as cool.

First off - 10 AAA batteries required between the 2 sets of robots/controllers (batteries not included). That's alot of AAA batteries - to appease the angry mob I was able to scrounge up enough AAA's after cannibalizing various devices around the house. Once batteries loaded and units operational my kids headed into battle. Basically the remote controllers let you have your robot spin it's arms to the left or the right - the turbo wheel makes them spin faster. No walking function except the spinning does cause the robot to creep around the floor - spin away and try and knock the other robot over. For whatever reason my daughter seemed to win more often than her big bro (as expected he blamed his robot as being inferior). I was actually impressed with build quality - rugged plastic beefed up to better survive physical combat.

What could be better:
-Remote controls have weak signal and the kids needed to be within a few feet of the robots to consistently control the robots.
-Replayability - my kids got pretty bored of this pretty fast - they quit playing after an hour and haven't tried again since. Thus I'm going to say ideal ages are younger than 9.
-Functionality - would be more fun to have more controllable features on the robots - some type of controllable mobility. Perhaps a nerf rocket you could launch remotely.

In summary - good build quality, takes too many batteries, limited ability to control robots, replayability probably best for kids under 9. At $50 current price kinda pricey considering all these factors though around the same price of a new release video game if you think of it that way - overall rating from me is 3-STARS in consideration of price/value.

'halder'(The company's name) is embedded on the charm's backs, which are unpainted. The characters themselves look fantastic, and the only minor complaint i have is that Polnareff's tanktop is pink on the keychain, when in the show it's a dark blue/black. Other than that, it's a solid 5 stars.

product_title: TECHEGE Toys Police Range Rover - Luxury Stealth Police Range Rover - Realistic Lights and Sounds
review_body:
The police range rover arrived broken for me, and it honestly took me a bit to care to fix it without having to return it. The problem was the motor was improperly set when it was manufactured so I had to put it back into place and snap the plastic housing that holds it together to spin a wheel.

After that was all said and done, this toy takes 3xAA batteries to power some lights and a motor to have the car drive, bump into something then change directions to bump into something else. The police siren is loud and the toy itself is pretty simple. I'm disappointed in this specific car as it looks pretty cheap and seems overpriced at $30. I recently reviewed another Techege police toy that transformed and that at least did something more interesting where my daughter enjoyed playing with it. This toy does not drive on carpet well so unless you have mostly hardwood/tile floors you won't get much out of it.

I received this complimentary free police range rover for testing and my unbiased and honest review.
